<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Korean Won Hits New Low Against U.S. Dollar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 19 (Xinhua) -- South Korean won tumbled to a
new low Friday, breaking the 910-won level for the first time as
the U.S. dollar surged against major currencies.
</P>
<P>
The won started today's trading at 910 won to the dollar, and
then slid to 913.30 won in the morning trading.
</P>
<P>
After a series of interventions by the Bank of Korea (BOK), the
South Korean currency stopped its fall at around the 912-won
level, the highest since the nation introduced an average market
rate system in March 1990.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean monetary unit has depreciated by 7.5 percent
against the U.S. banknote since the end of last year, when the
won-dollar parity rate stood at 844.20.
</P>
<P>
"To keep the foreign exchange rate stable, we will continue to
strongly intervene to sell U.S. currency in both spot and forward
trading," said Lee Eung-baek, chief of BOK's Foreign Exchange
Division, adding that BOK would not let the won fall further.
</P>
<P>
Foreign currency dealers attributed the won's continuous fall
against the dollar to the latter's strength against the Japanese
yen in international foreign exchange markets, and the high demand
for dollars by domestic businesses in imports settling.
</P>
<P>
They also cited the Japanese banks' moves to temporarily
collect their short-term, foreign currency loans to South Korean
banks in order to meet the capital adequacy ratio recommended by
the Bank for International Settlements.
</P>
<P>
Despite a strong supply of dollar by the South Korean central
bank, concerns over the possibility of a credit crunch resulting
from recent bankruptcies and financial troubles at major domestic
conglomerates continue to weigh on the South Korean currency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
