<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonn, Paris Still at Odds over Unemployment, EU Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The 70th Franco-German summit
ended today in the historic eastern German town of Weimar leaving
differences unresolved over such issues as unemployment and the
European Union reforms, despite a strong show of unity in efforts
towards a peaceful and powerful Europe.
</P>
<P>
Both Germany and France stressed the importance of the upcoming
November EU meeting in Luxembourg on employment. German Chancellor
Helmut Kohl told a news conference after separate talks today with
French President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
that the two countries would hold intensive talks on the
unemployment issue.
</P>
<P>
On how to combat Europe's high unemployment, Germany has been
opposing new EU spending for any job program, deeming job
creation largely a national task. However, Prime Minister Jospin,
known to favor state-run job schemes, has been urging concerted
EU action.
</P>
<P>
Germany is now suffering from a postwar high jobless rate of
11.4 percent, and France's unemployment is currently 12.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the news conference, President Chirac made it clear that
Paris would hold firmly on to its position that the EU
institutional reform should be given priority to taking in new
members.
</P>
<P>
"These reforms are a prerequisite for expansion -- and if they
do not come then there will be no expansion," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kohl however noted that reforms and expansion were not
contradictory in principle and should go on at the same time.
</P>
<P>
As expected, the three leaders all reaffirmed that the single
European currency, the euro, would be introduced on time in 1999
and according to the stability criteria.
</P>
<P>
Germany and France, two partners at the center of European
integration, have been feared to miss the economic targets to
qualify for the euro, forcing postponement of the project.
However, signs of economic upturn in Europe have eased the
worries.
</P>
<P>
Concerning their differences over the future European central
bank, Kohl said: " We are completely sure that we will be able to
find out a reasonable solution."
</P>
<P>
Germany has been in favor of an independent central bank while
Paris enjoying to see political control over it.
</P>
<P>
Saying that France also hoped for an independent central bank,
Jospin added it was important that all EU countries joining the
euro should achieve a better coordination of their economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day consultations, France and Germany agreed to
expand cooperation in the fields of telecommunications and
aerospace.
</P>
<P>
Apparently moving closer on the issue of reforming Europe's
Airbus Industrie into a for-profit company, both sides agreed to
give "a European response" to the merger between American aviation
giants Boeing and McDonnell Douglas.
</P>
<P>
German media reports quoted a French government source as
saying that the transformation of the four-nation Airbus
consortium would be realized by January 1999.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also agreed during the summit that their two
telecom companies should buy a 7.5 percent stake in each other.
</P>
<P>
As one of the concrete achievements of the summit, foreign
ministers of the two countries today signed the establishment of a
joint Franco-German university with a view to harmonizing
university studies in the two countries and to mutually
recognizing degrees.
</P>
<P>
At the news conference, the leaders all stressed that the
future cooperation between their two countries was crucial.
</P>
<P>
Germany and France must once again provide a new thrust to
bring Europe forward, said Kohl.  
</P>
</TEXT>
