<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading U.S. newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Spraying gunfire and hurling a bomb, at least two
assailants attacked a tour bus in Cairo and killed 10 people.
Egyptian officials insisted the attack was not the resurgence of
an Islamic militant campaign.
</P>
<P>
-- The number AIDS cases diagnosed in the United States
dropped last year for the first time in the history of the
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Militant Jewish settlers agreed to vacate their home in an
Arab neighborhood in East Jerusalem in a compromise reached this
evening with the Israeli government, but Palestinian officials
condemned the deal as the compromise permit Jewish students to
take the place of the departing families.
</P>
<P>
-- Business leaders are planning to spend at least $2 million
on an air and land war to persuade Congress to broaden President
Clinton's trade negotiating powers
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, adding her voice to
the Clinton administration's push for passage of trade
legislation, called the measure a "foreign policy imperative"
needed to maintain world leadership.
</P>
<P>
-- Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said global investors
aren't suffering enough for their unwise investments in
countries like Mexico and Thailand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
