<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Catholic Church to Apologize to Jews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The Roman Catholic Church of
France will apologize to Jews for the silence it maintained when
German Nazi occupiers deported tens of thousand of French Jews to
death camps during the Vichy collaboration period from 1941 to
1944.
</P>
<P>
This will be the first time for the French Catholic Church to
formally recognize its wartime anti-Semitic attitude and behavior.
</P>
<P>
The church has been blamed in the past for offering hideouts to
former Nazi collaborators, such as former chief of the Lyon
militiamen, Paul Touvier, who hid in a church compound in southern
France for more than 40 years.
</P>
<P>
Although some bishops and priests tried to protect and help
Jews from 1942, most church priests remained silent and failed to
speak out when Nazi atrocities took place, said Jean Dujardin,
secretary of the church's espiscopal committee in charge of
relations with Judaism.
</P>
<P>
A communique published by the French Catholic Church today said
that several prominent figures of the church will attend a
ceremony on September 30 at the former site of the concentration
camp of Drancy outside Paris, from where 64,000 Jews were
transported to death camps in Germany and Nazi occupied countries.
</P>
<P>
Archbishop Jean-Marie Lustiger of Paris and the President of
the Episcopal Conference of France, Louis-Marie Bille, as well as
bishops of the Paris region and French departments where Jews were
rounded up and deported.
</P>
<P>
A declaration by the bishops of France on the "attitude of the
bishops of France during the war" will be read by Bishop Olivier
de Berranger of Saint-Denis, a city outside Paris.
</P>
<P>
He will try to tell "to which degree had the negative vision
on Jews that the Church had carried for centuries helped prepare a
field in which the Nazi ideas could have established themselves
without resistance" during World War II in France.
</P>
<P>
French historian Pierre Pierrard said in his book "Jews and
French Catholics" that the church welcomed anti-Semitic laws
drafted by Marshal Petain in 1940, which cast out the Jews from
the French society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Communist Party Congratulates Jiang on Re-election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The Communist Party of
Vietnam (CPV) today congratulated Jiang Zemin on his re-election
as the top leader of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
Do Muoi, general secretary of the CPV Central Committee, sent a
message to Jiang, who was re-elected earlier in the day as the
general secretary of the CPC's Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Under CPC's leadership headed by Jiang, Do said in the message,
the Chinese people are sure to score more achievements in their
drive to build socialism with Chinese characteristics.
</P>
<P>
He praised the Chinese leader's contributions to consolidating
and promoting the traditional friendly and good neighborly ties
between the two parties, the two countries and the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
The CPV leader also wished the Sino-Vietnamese mutual trust and
understanding, and bilateral relations be further strengthened,
and Jiang accomplish greater achievements in the future.
</P>
<P>
Jiang was re-elected to his post at the First Plenum of the
15th CPC Central Committee at the Great Hall of the People here
this morning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
