<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook Reiterates UK Stance on EMU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 19 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook today reiterated Britain's stance towards European
economic and monetary union (EMU), saying Britain is unlikely to
join the union at the outset in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on BBC radio, Cook said that Britain is unlikely to be
among the founding members of EMU.
</P>
<P>
"We've always said that it is unlikely Britain will be joining,
partly because we are a new government with a big agenda to do,"
Cook said.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that if the single currency goes ahead
and if it is a success, then in the longer term it will be
difficult for Britain to stay out.
</P>
<P>
Cook added that Britain will not make its decision about
whether to join in 1999 until around the turn of the year, because
"it has to be based on the outturn figures for this year".
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that the positive tone towards EMU shown in the
recent remarks of senior ministers reflected Prime Minister
Blair's desire not to stand in the way of other European Union
(EU) countries that are determined to launch EMU.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, as Britain will hold the rotating EU presidency in
the upper half of next year, it is keen to retain influence over
the planned EMU even if it does not join itself right now.
</P>
</TEXT>
