<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-19 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Euro-Parliament Resolution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus today welcomed and
expressed its satisfaction with a resolution on Cyprus passed by
the European Parliament Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Government Spokesman Manolis Christofides said at a press
briefing that the resolution covered all aspects of the Cyprus
problem and referred to all necessary measures to be taken to help
solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, tabled by all political groups in the European
Parliament, denounced the joint declaration signed by the Turkish
Cypriot and Turkey in July as "illegal, provocative and not
conducing to creating the right negotiating climate for the talks
on Cyprus."
</P>
<P>
"We consider it as one of the best resolutions ever approved on
the Cyprus problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
The declaration of the Turkish Cypriots and Turkey calls for
"gradual economic and financial integration and partial
integration on security, defense and foreign policy matters"
between both sides.
</P>
<P>
The European Parliament's resolution criticized the stance of
the Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash to the U.N.-sponsored
peace talks last month aimed at resolving the protracted Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Denktash reportedly set the freezing of accession negotiations
between Cyprus and the European Union, scheduled early next year,
as a precondition to progress in the talks.
</P>
<P>
The resolution welcomed the outcome of the recent meetings
between President Glafcos Clerides and Denktash in Nicosia on
humanitarian issues and measures concerning investigations into
the fate of the missing people of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
It also welcomed the recent announcement that Clerides and
Denktash will meet again to discuss security issues.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when
Turkey landed its troops on the east Mediterranean island and
took over the northern third in the wake of a failed coup by the
Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece. The Turkish Cypriots
declared in 1983 a breakaway "Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus"
which is recognized only by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations and the international community have been
trying for decades to reunite the island as a bi-communal,
bi-zonal federation through peace talks, but no tangible results
have so far been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
