<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Kicks off Poverty Alleviation Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government
released Thursday more than 10 million U.S. Dollars for the
take-off of its Family Economic Advancement Program (FEAP) to
reinforce the poverty alleviation effort.
</P>
<P>
The program, according to FEAP Director-General Abdullahi
Aliyu, is aimed to create one million jobs and establish 7,500
cottage industries mainly in the rural areas every year.
</P>
<P>
These activities are expected to contribute about two percent
to the gross national product annually between 1998 and 2010,
Aliyu told a news briefing in the capital of Abuja Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government, which puts high hope on the program, has
budgeted 4.3 billion Naira (about 51 million U.S. Dollars) for
its execution this year.
</P>
<P>
The sum of 1.07 billion Naira, or about 13 million U.S.
Dollars, released Thursday is the first part of it.
</P>
<P>
According to the director-general, the money will facilitate
the take-off the job creation scheme which involves granting
about 500,000 Naira loan to private investors for establishing
one cottage industry across the country.
</P>
<P>
The cottage industries will be set up and run on a family
basis, which will use the abundant local raw materials and
agricultural produce to produce goods suitable for the local
market.
</P>
<P>
To ensure smooth implementation of the program, FEAP has been
set up as a government agency according to a decree earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
Henceforth all agencies providing loans to individuals and
organizations for small industries will now channel their funds
through FEAP to harmonize loan disbursement.
</P>
<P>
The loans to be channeled to the full-fledged parastatal
include those given by the national directorate of employment,
People's Bank of Nigeria, Ministry of Industries and other
ministries.
</P>
<P>
A 20-member governing board has set up the program with
Nigeria's first lady, Mrs. Maryam Sani Abacha as the patron.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
