<HEADLINE> Road Accidents Cost Nigeria Heavily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria loses about 20 billion
Naira (about 240 million U.S. dollars) a year to road accidents,
according to a government official.
</P>
<P>
The losses arose from medicine, hospital equipment and vehicle
spare parts to repair damaged vehilces, Alhaji Baba Gana Ibrahim,
deputy director of the national uniform licensing scheme, said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The official did not disclose how many road accidents took
place in a year, but blamed about 80 percent of them on the human
factor, particularly the incompetence of most drivers, beside
vehicular and environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
At a national road traffic regulation workshop, the official
urged state road traffic officers to implement the government's
road-worthy certificate scheme for vehicles effectively.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, vehicle owners will be given certificates
after their vehicles have been inspected.
</P>
<P>
The official said this would help ensure that only
well-maintained vehicles plied the nation's roads as part of
efforts to check the rate of accidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
