<HEADLINE> Illegal Diamond Mining Condemned in Sierra Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chief Secretary of State in the military government Solomon
Musa said,"Some of the security personnel have even taken over
the whole chiefdom, chased out authorized officials of the
Department of Mineral Resources and are issuing tickets for
mining licenses and diamond plots."
</P>
<P>
Solomon Musa condemned in no uncertain terms this behavior of
the officers concerned and hereby warned them to desist from this
ugly practice with immediate effect, or face very severe
disciplinary action, state radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said the statement is "a radical departure from
past positions taken by the government on diamond mining in the
country."
</P>
<P>
According to the observers, "The government has taken a bold
move to name some members of the RUF, which is now in alliance
with the military since the May 25 coup, as perpetrators in
illegal diamond mining which has been free for all even under the
ousted civilian government of Tejan Kabbah."
</P>
<P>
A Sierra Leonean geologist said Sierra Leone produces about
one million carats of diamonds every year but many of these are
smuggled out through Guinea and Liberia and are not reflected in
official records.
</P>
<P>
Many of the miners are Nigerians, Gambians, Senegalese and
Malians as well as Lebanese. 
</P>
