<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Unionists Urge Renewal of EU/ACP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Southern Africa's trade
unionists today said the Lome IV Convention, a preferential trade
arrangement between developing countries and the EU due to expire
in 2000, should be renewed and strengthened.
</P>
<P>
A joint Commonwealth Trade Union Coordinating Council (CTUC)
believed that the convention is unique as it provides " a
progressive framework for the developing world in the face of the
global free market drive".
</P>
<P>
The unions from the 10 southern African countries were
examining the future of the African, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP)
countries after Lome IV Convention during a five-day workshop
which ended here today.
</P>
<P>
Lome IV Convention "should be renewed and strengthened beyond
the year 2000". The big difference from other trade bloc
agreements around the world is that Lome IV Convention has a big
potential to help developing countries tackle economic
globalization, said Gibson Sibanda, a CTUC executive member.
</P>
<P>
He said Lome also underpins sustainable development because it
combines preferential trade, development and aid packages with
partner organizations.
</P>
<P>
The World Trade Organization, he said, is not a sufficient
solution for human progress in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Other conclusions reached include that Lome IV Convention's
future is critical to southern Africa in areas such as
preferential trade and development cooperation with the EU.
</P>
<P>
The delegates held that it is also essential to maintain the
bloc of ACP countries together to negotiate in unity and
solidarity with the EU and that Lome should have the values of
cooperation, partnership and human rights for better economic and
social progress.
</P>
<P>
They pointed out Lome IV Convention has not reached its full
potential in such areas as human resource development, education
and training, women and gender issues and the environment.
</P>
<P>
Unions were urged to shape a role and strategy that
will contribute to the priorities of Lome plans and projects by
working with governments and other organizations in civil
society.
</P>
<P>
The Lome Convention is the comprehensive trade, aid and
development agreement between the 15 countries in the EU and 71
countries in the ACP.
</P>
<P>
The convention is currently being reviewed and the EU has
launched a debate on the issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
