<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Airlifts Food to Pointe Noire of Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP)
today began airlifting emergency food for 60,600 displaced people
in Congo's Pointe Noire area.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here today said that the first WFP
Boeing 727 carrying 16 tons of beans and oil touched down this
morning in Pointe Noire, second largest city in Congo after
Brazzaville.
</P>
<P>
Between today and tomorrow, WFP will make a total of 8
flights, delivering 132 tons of beans and oil to the area where
there are already cereal stocks of 1,300 tons.
</P>
<P>
The release noted that the cereal stocks to be used as a
one-month distribution package would be distributed beginning
from Monday to the extremely vulnerable people in the area, who
have fled from the Brazzaville area.
</P>
<P>
The original population of Brazzaville is estimated at 900,000
and 250,000 of this population still remain in the city.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the Brazzaville population have fled to the
south of the country and about 300,000 could be in the southern
provinces including the Pointe Noire area.
</P>
<P>
Another 150,000 people are believed to have moved northward,
but they are virtually inaccessible to aid agencies due to the
on-going conflict, the release said.
</P>
<P>
WFP has originally planned to send the beans and oil for the
Pointe Noire people to Kinshasa by river barge, but low water
levels on some passages of the river have caused the barges
stranded.
</P>
<P>
In view of this situation, WFP has quickly responded by
mounting an airlift directly to Pointe Noire from Luanda, Angola
and barges will continue their journey once the water level
of the river rises.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week, WFP airlifted 87 tons of beans and oil from
Luanda to Kinshasa in five flights for the 28,000 refugees in
Kinshasa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
