<HEADLINE> Crashed Planes' Pieces Collected From Sea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Burned pieces, deflated
life-jackets and personal effects from two planes have been
unloaded at Namibia's western port city of Walvis Bay.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here today said the items, from one of the
two military planes believed to have collided off the Namibian
coast last Saturday, were brought to Walvis Bay by a fishing
vessel which travelled 33 hours from the scene.
</P>
<P>
It is not yet known if the burnt pieces belong to the German
military plane or the American air force transport aircraft,
which crashed over the south Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
An international sea and air search mission from South Africa,
France, Germany and the United States has been combing the crash
area since the collision occurred last week.
</P>
<P>
Only a woman body believed to be from the German plane was
found on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A South African air force spokesman said today that weather
conditions have improved in the searching area, giving the
operation better chances of success.
</P>
<P>
New search areas have been identified and eight aircraft are
scouting for wreckage, possible survivors or bodies, he added.
</P>
<P>
The German plane was carrying 24 people to South Africa. The
U.S. aircraft, with nine crew members on board, was on its way
home from Namibia where it had dropped mine-clearing equipment.
</P>
</TEXT>
