<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique to Increase Education Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The government plans to
increase its financial allocation to education from the present
17 percent of its budget to 22-25 percent in the coming years in
a bid to implement its "strategic program" for education.
</P>
<P>
This was announced here today by Arnoldo Nhavoto, Minister of
Education at a regular news briefing.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not reveal the specific percentage or amount
of money involved, saying that it depends on which plan will be
carried out for the "strategic program".
</P>
<P>
Under the first plan, the enrolment rate for first grade
student in primary school is to grow from the current 75 percent
to 86 in the year 2000, and to 95 percent in 2006, to 100 percent
in the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
The second plan sees a faster growth, which stipulates the
increase of enrolment rate to 90 percent in the year 2000, 95
percent in 2006, and 100 percent in 2010.
</P>
<P>
In Mozambique, children of six year old may go to school.
However, due to limited classrooms, many kids cannot go to school
until after the prescribed age. Only 15 percent of the newly
enrolled 300,000 kids go to school at six.
</P>
<P>
Nhavoto disclosed that the 16 years of civil war has destroyed
60 percent of school buildings. Only 40 percent of schools were
still operating in 1992, when the peace agreement was signed, he
said.
</P>
<P>
With efforts made by the government, 96.7 percent of school
buildings have been rehabilitated, he said, adding it is
estimated that all schools would be restored in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the number of students from grade
one to four in primary schools have increased from 1.2 million in
1992 to the present 1.7 million.
</P>
<P>
The government will also enhance quality education through
improving school buildings and educational equipment, as well as
teachers' training, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
