<HEADLINE> FAO Pledges Aid to Ethiopia's Irrigation Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Jacques Diouf, director
general of the United Nations Food and Agriculture Organization
(FAO) who is currently visiting here, today pledged FAO's
assistance to Ethiopia's small-scale irrigation program.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency reported that, in his talks with
Ethiopian Prime Minister Meles Zenawi, Diouf said Ethiopian
agriculture is almost entirely rain-fed and as a result, it is
persistently affected by erratic natural phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
FAO is ready to assist Ethiopia in the implementation of the
small-scale irrigation program to bring the country's agriculture
out of its extreme dependence on rain, Diouf noted.
</P>
<P>
The program is an outcome of an agreement between Ethiopia,
China and the FAO, and will be first implemented in arid regions
of the Amhara and Tigray National States of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia currently irrigates about 3 percent of its
potentially irrigable land, compared with the 50 percent by
China, which feeds one-fifth of the world's population with only
7 percent of the world's arable land.
</P>
<P>
The FAO chief arrived here today for a two-day visit. He also
met with Ethiopian President Negasso Gidada today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
