<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-19 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Government, Military Discuss Missile </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Turkish government officials
and the senior generals today discussed the threat of the S-300
missiles to be purchased by Cyprus, vowing to block the missile
transfer with all necessary means.
</P>
<P>
The General Staff officials, including Deputy Chief of General
Staff Cevik Bir, briefed Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz and other
Cabinet members on the latest development on the Cypriot missile
program, according to the semi-official Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The possible delivery of the S-300 missiles purchased by Greek
Cypriots from Russia has constituted a serious threat to the state
security of Turkey itself, the military officials said.
</P>
<P>
The officials urged the government to take all possible methods
to block the transfer of the anti-aircraft missiles to the Cypriot
government.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported recently that the Russian-made missiles
would be transported into the eastern Mediterranean island soon,
causing grave concern from the Turkish government.
</P>
<P>
If all diplomatic efforts end fruitless, the last option of
the counter-measures is to destroy these offensive missiles, the
military officials said.
</P>
<P>
After the military briefing on the Cypriot missile program,
Yilmaz told the press that the Turkish government would not allow
the deployment of the S-300 missiles in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The missiles can be turned into offensive weapons with slight
modifications, Turkey will not remain indifferent to this
development, Yilmaz said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the government and the General Staff would
cooperate closely to block the delivery of the surface-to-air
missiles to the Greek Cypriot side.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish prime minister also urged Russia to take a
sensitive stance, saying its missile deal with Greek Cypriots
will endanger not only Turkish Cypriots' but also Turkey's
security.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that the Turkish army and police should tighten
security measures in the air space and in the Turkish Straits to
block the missile delivery.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government purchases around 150 S-300 missiles
from a Russian industrial company in accordance with a deal
signed last year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has repeatedly accusing the Cypriot government of
buying such missiles from Russia, vowing to lauch a military
strike on the weapons if necessary.
</P>
<P>
The Cypriot government, however, argued that it imported the
Russian-made missiles for defense purpose, adding these missiles
are not directed against any country.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has remained divided since 1974 when Turkish troops
landed on the island and took over the northern third of it
following a pro-Athens coup by Greek Cypriots. A breakaway
republic was set up by Turkish Cypriots in northern Cyprus, which
is only recognized by Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
