<HEADLINE> Turkey's Islamists Protest New Education Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's conservative
Islamists today continued their Friday demonstrations to protest
the newly adopted eight-year compulsory education law.
</P>
<P>
Around 700 protesters gathered outside the Beyazit Mosque in
Turkey's largest city of Istanbul after their prayer services,
shouting anti-government slogans.
</P>
<P>
They, dispersed by the security police, demanded for revision
of the education law and continuous operation of the religious
schools.
</P>
<P>
In central Turkey's Konya, the stronghold of the pro-Islamic
Welfare Party, a group of Islamists rallied on the street,
shouting slogans against the law.
</P>
<P>
Some protesters clashed with the police in Adiyaman in
southeastern Turkey, and 40 people were taken into custody for
disobeying police disperse orders.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's conservative Islamists stared to hold anti-government
demonstrations every Friday after the Parliament approved the law
in August.
</P>
<P>
Under the law, a large number of religious schools will be shut
down, which is regarded as a heavy blow to the conservative
religious force.
</P>
<P>
The education reform launched by the Yilmaz government, with
the support of the military, is aimed at curbing the rapidly
growing fundamentalism in the secular republic. 
</P>
