<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0048 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Advocacy Group Says "Brady Law" Helps Reduce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 19 (Xinhua) -- States that require
background checks on prospective handgun purchasers are reducing
interstate gun trafficking in the United States, says a study by
The Center to Prevent Handgun Violence.
</P>
<P>
The organization said Friday that figures from the federal
Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms shows that checks and
waiting periods required by the so-called "Brady law" had a major
and positive effect.
</P>
<P>
"This research demonstrates that the law that carries my
husband's name is doing even more than it was designed to do in
keeping guns out of the hands of criminals," Sarah Brady, the
center's chairwoman, said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Sarah's husband, James Brady, was the former White House press
secretary. He was wounded with President Reagan in an
assassination attempt on the president in 1981.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-eight states have their own Brady laws and many law
enforcement officials in the others have continued the checks.
</P>
<P>
The Center to Prevent Handgun Violence found that states
requiring checks since the Brady law went into effect in 1994 are
up to 86 percent less likely to be sources of guns used in crimes
in other states than they were prior to the law's enactment.
</P>
<P>
The study covered the period between 1989 and January 1997.
</P>
<P>
"It is clear that the Brady law has helped to keep guns out of
the hands of thousands of criminals and others who are not
competent to possess a firearm," said R. Gil Kerlikowske, Buffalo,
New York, police commissioner and president of the Police
Executive Research Forum.
</P>
<P>
The study focused on four states -- Ohio, Kentucky, Mississippi
and Georgia -- where data suggested handguns were easy to purchase
before Brady Law was enacted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month thee Justice Department reported that police
background checks blocked 173,000 illegal handgun sales since
enactment of the Brady law, including 70,000 in 1996 alone.
</P>
<P>
The Supreme Court ruled in June that the federal government
could not force state and local authorities to conduct Brady's
background checks, but left intact its five-day waiting period for
a handgun purchase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
