<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> APEC Ministers Support Small Business Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Ministers from 18 economies of
Asia Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) agreed here today to take
measures that will benefit small and medium-sized enterprises
(SMEs).
</P>
<P>
"Ministers committed to strengthen the SME Agenda and to
provide policies and activities that will provide meaningful
results to SMEs," said a joint statement released at the end of
the Fourth APEC Ministers' Meeting on SMEs.
</P>
<P>
SMEs comprise over 90 percent of all enterprises in the Asia
Pacific region and contribute between 30-60 percent of GDP of APEC
economies.
</P>
<P>
They generate about 35 percent of the region's exports and
account for 32-84 percent of employment in APEC economies.
</P>
<P>
Yet, due to their relatively small size, most SMEs encounter a
lot of difficulties in penetrating new markets and developing the
necessary skills and technology to improve their competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meeting, the ministers reached consensus on
a framework for APEC SME activities to benefit small businesses.
</P>
<P>
The framework will be presented to the APEC economic leaders
for adoption at their summit slated for November in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
"Our objective is to provide solutions to help SMEs and remove
barriers to their growth," John Manley, Canada's industry minister
and chairman of the ministerial meeting, told a press conference
here today.
</P>
<P>
"We have laid the groundwork for a more dynamic contribution by
SMEs to each APEC economy, and their greater contribution to
international trade within the region," said Manley, who was
flanked by other APEC ministers.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, five issues of particular importance to
SMEs were discussed at the meeting, namely access to markets,
technology, human resources, financing and information.
</P>
<P>
On access to markets, the ministers called for harmonization of
standards, customs procedures, professional qualifications,
investment laws and taxation procedures.
</P>
<P>
On access to technology, the ministers agreed that information
and communications technologies can provide opportunities for SMEs
in a knowledge-based economy. They welcomed initiatives to
transfer technology from industrialized to developing countries.
</P>
<P>
On access to human resources, the ministers discussed the
implications of an emerging knowledge-based economy on the need
for constant training and skills upgrading for SMEs in both
developed and developing countries and welcomed initiatives on
this regard.
</P>
<P>
On access to financing, they reviewed the results of a recent
consultation of APEC business associations and welcomed the
initiatives of the export credit agencies to take the lead in
exploring measures to support SME exporters.
</P>
<P>
On access to information, the ministers agreed that APEC can
and will make the greatest near-term contribution to SMEs by
providing accurate and timely information to help SMEs compete in
the global market.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from the APEC business community contributed
their ideas on the five issues through a business forum attended
by some 1,000 delegates from the region.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the ministers also received input from women
leaders, young entrepreneurs, business support associations and
the APEC Business Advisory Council.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1989, the APEC forum is a group of Pacific Rim
economies working together to promote open trade, investment, and
economic and technological cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Its members are Australia; Brunei Darussalam; Canada; Chile;
the People's Republic of China; Hong Kong, China; Indonesia;, Japan;
the Republic of Korea; Malaysia; Mexico; New Zealand; Papua New
Guinea; the Republic of the Philippines; Singapore; Chinese Taipei;
Thailand; and the United States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Electric Corp to Reduce Power Supply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Electric
Corporation announced today that it has decided to reduce power
supply due to low volume of water reserves at two of its three
dams.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here, Mehret Dibaba, deputy general
manager for the corporation's operation sector, said the amount
of water that entered the Koka and Melkawakena dams during this
year's rainy season (June to September) has been very low
compared to that of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The in-flow to the two dams is therefore reduced by 43 and 33
percent respectively, causing energy crisis in the corporation's
interconnected power system for the coming months.
</P>
<P>
This, Dibaba said, has dictated the corporation's decision for
the alternate disruption of power supply with a view to
economizing what is available, and all month distribution of
power supply for fixed hours a week during 1997 to 1998 across
the country.
</P>
<P>
He thus urged the public and administrations of factories and
organizations to make frugal use of power supply, thereby joining
hands in the corporation's bid to effectively utilize power that
could be generated throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia enforced a 13-hours weekly power cut from December
1995 to June 1996. The emergency measure was lifted in June last
year following good rains at the dams of the hydro-power
stations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Congressmen Support Canadians Exempt From Border Checks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 19 (Xinhua) -- More U.S. Congressmen
support Canadians in being exempted from a law that calls for
extensive tracking of every entry and exit of visitors to the
United States, a Senate spokesman said today.
</P>
<P>
"There has yet to emerge an opponent to exempting Canada,"
said Steve Hessler, a spokesman for Senator Spencer Abraham, who
chairs the Senate subcommittee on immigration.
</P>
<P>
The subcommittee is exploring methods to exempt Canadians from
the law, Hessler said.
</P>
<P>
The law, which was signed by President Bill Clinton a year ago,
requires the Immigration and Naturalization Service (INS) to
create a system by next September to track the entry and exit of
foreigners in order to crack down on people living in the U.S.
illegally.
</P>
<P>
The law has been intensely criticized by Canadians, who are
concerned that the system will mean long lines at the border.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Canadians paid more than 50 million trips to the
U.S., according to the Canadian authorities.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials at the U.S.-Canadian border ask visitors what
their nationality is and often just wave them in with only a
question or two. Visitors are not stopped on their way out of the
U.S. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 091954 Zambian President Blames Europe for Conflicts in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Lusaka, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba today blamed European countries for the internal
conflicts now sweeping through Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said in Kitwe, northern Zambia, that the rule of law in any
country is the strongest foundation for peace and it took Europe
over 1,000 years to democratize and that the African continent
was only decolonialized about 40 years ago, therefore it should not
be expected to be a conflict free zone.
</P>
<P>
When he opened a workshop on peace building strategy in a
civil society, he said "Europe took over 1,000 years to
democratize, how do they expect Africa to do this in less than 40
years. I blame them for most of these African conflicts."
</P>
<P>
The Zambia National Broadcasting Corporation Television quoted
him as saying that Africa has a long way to go before the
conflicts are fully managed but its people must start by
understanding that only a popularly elected government has the
right of power to rule the sovereign state.
</P>
<P>
He warned that absence of the rule of law in any country is a
recipe for internal conflict.
</P>
<P>
The other major contributor to the conflicts in Africa, added
Chiluba, is the slave trade by European nations.
</P>
<P>
Despite historical background, he said, Africa is now fully
responsible for what is happening on its continent now as much as
Zambians are responsible for what is occurring here.
</P>
<P>
The president said his government will not relent on its
mission of establishing institutions that contribute to peace
such as the human rights commission. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
