<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US, Japan Agree on Defense Guidelines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The United States and
Japan have agreed on U.S.-Japan defense guidelines, which provide
the framework for Tokyo to give key military support to American
forces whenever the two countries consider there is a crisis in
Asia, the Pentagon said today.
</P>
<P>
"The defense guidelines... provide guidance for our political
leadership and for our military planners in terms of roles and
missions, about how the United States and Japan would respond in a
crisis -- a crisis that challenges Japan and a crisis in the
surrounding arena," said Kurt Campbell, the Pentagon's deputy
assistant secretary for Asian and Pacific affairs.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Defense Secretary
William Cohen will meet with their Japanese counterparts next week
in New York for the culmination of almost two years of work on the
revision of the U.S.-Japan defense guidelines, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
Eastern Asian countries are wary of any offensive use of
Japan's large and high-tech Self-Defense Force in the region
despite Japan's pledge to abide by restriction of its Constitution
against such deployment.
</P>
<P>
There are 47,000 American troops stationed in Japan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Inflation Rate Remains Steady </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Canadian consumers paid an
average of 1.8 percent more in August for the goods and services
included in the Consumer Price Index (CPI) basket from a year
earlier, Statistics Canada said today.
</P>
<P>
This annual rate of price increase was identical to those
reported for June and July, the federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
Canadian consumers have paid more for transportation in the
form of higher gasoline prices, vehicle insurance premiums, new
vehicle prices and air fares since August last year.
</P>
<P>
They also paid more for food, clothing, university tuition,
cigarettes, and telephone services.
</P>
<P>
However, they benefited from lower interest rates when they
renewed mortgage loans and bought big-ticket items, the agency
said.
</P>
<P>
Between July and August, Canadian consumers paid more for
gasoline, clothing, footwear and alcoholic beverages and food. The
net effect was a 0.1 percent rise in the CPI. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
