<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Says No New Food Aid to DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The United States said
today that it did not offer new aid food to the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) in connection with four-party
peace talks in New York.
</P>
<P>
"We have not and will not link North Korea's participation in
the four-party talks to other issues including food and therefore
the U.S. has made no such proposal (of new food aid)," State
Department spokesman James Rubin said at a regular briefing.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to earlier speculation that Washington and
Seoul had proposed 100,000 tons of monthly food aid to the DPRK as
Pyongyang was willing to attend the four-party peace talks in New
York.
</P>
<P>
Rubin told reporters that there had been no change in U.S.
policy for that matter.
</P>
<P>
"Decisions on food assistance are based on humanitarian
reasons. We do not use food as a political weapon. American food
aid to North Korea and four-party talks are independent of each
other. No change in that policy has been or is being
contemplated," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
