<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eight People Died of Snake Bites in Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Eight people died in
Hager Mariam district, southern Ethiopia, after being bitten by
poisonous snakes which were supposedly taking refuge nearby
residential houses to escape the unusually scorching sun.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency reported today that 18 people,
including the eight dead, have been bitten since mid-July.
</P>
<P>
The number of fatalities from snake bites has dramatically
increased this year, the report noted, quoting local residents as
saying that unlike in the past when snakes simply fled to avoid
human presence, they now become aggressive and turn on people who
try to chase them away.
</P>
<P>
Similarly four people died of bites by rabid dogs in same
district, the report said, adding that there has not been any
confirmation whether the incident has anything to do with the
rise in the temperature this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
