<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Staff Airlifted From North Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 20 (Xinhua) -- U.N. staff and foreign aid
workers trapped in Afghanistan's beleaguered town of
Mazar-e-Sharif, around 300 kilometers north of Kabul, were
airlifted to Pakistan today, a U.N. official said.
</P>
<P>
Two U.N. planes were sent to Afghanistan's northern military
garrison of Shibarghan and neighboring Uzbekstan to fetch 15 U.N.
employees and three international aid workers, said Sarah Russell,
spokesperson for the U.N. Development Program (UNDP) for
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Two planes of the International Committee of the Red Cross
(ICRC) have flown in 35 foreign aid workers to Islamabad so far.
</P>
<P>
"We have left essential staff in Mazar-e-Sharif and have not
suspended our operations," Russell said.
</P>
<P>
She said two foreigners and hundreds of Afghan employees of
various U.N. offices are still working in the stronghold of the
anti-Taliban alliance.
</P>
<P>
The stranded foreigners were flown out after Afghan warring
groups offered to hold fire if the United Nations wanted to
evacuate its staff and foreign aid workers.
</P>
<P>
They had been trapped in Mazar-e-Sharif since the Islamic
Taliban militia launched attack on the northern town early this
month.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban forces briefly held the airport of Mazar-e-Sharif,
about 18 kilometers east of the town but lost the control to the
opposition forces a few days after.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. officials, the U.N. offices in Mazar-e-Sharif
were ransacked and looted by gun-toting youth and losses are
estimated to run into millions of U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
