<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Urges Freeze of Normalization with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat today urged Arab states to freeze
normalization process with Israel until the Mideast peace march
makes progress.
</P>
<P>
In a strongly-worded address at the 108th session of the Arab
League foreign ministers council that opened here today, Arafat
said Arab participation in multilateral talks should be linked up
to bilateral talks between Arabs and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Calling for unifying Arab stance, he urged Arab countries to
implement the resolutions adopted at the 1996 Cairo Arab Summit
that recommended to freeze Arab-Israeli normalization until an
Israeli compliance with the peace commitment is realized.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said the Mideast peace process is facing a real crisis
because of Israel's anti-Arab policies and mass punitive measures
against the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"The Jewish state wishes to change Jerusalem's demographic
characteristics and impose a new status quo on the city before the
start of any future final settlement talks with the Palestinians,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
Arafat accused Israel of failing to honor any of its
obligations to redeploy its troops, open the safety passage and
crossing-points and release Palestinian detainees.
</P>
<P>
"Israel did not only pursue its settlement activities but also
deliberately continue to disown all peace agreements," he said,
adding that Israel denies the Palestinian right to existence in a
way that threatened the peace march.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations have been deadlocked
since Israel began the construction of a Jewish settlement in East
Jerusalem in March. The crisis heightened after suicide bombings
hit Jerusalem on July 30 and September 4, killing altogether 25
people and wounding more than 300 others.
</P>
<P>
After the bombings, Israel imposed harsh closure on the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, which caused losses of nearly 6 million
U.S. dollars a day for the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day meetings, 18 Arab foreign ministers are
expected to examine the destructive outcome of the Israeli
policies on the long-crumbling Mideast peace process and discuss
Israel's practices in occupied Arab territories, as well as the
cut of services to Palestinian refugees due to a financial crisis
facing the U.N. Relief and Works Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
