<HEADLINE> Iraq Welcomes Cooperation with Syria in Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Iraqi Tourist Authority
welcomed a proposed all-round and coordinated cooperation with
Syria in tourism, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
Authority chief Sirwan Abdul-Kader was quoted by the INA as
saying that Iraq is looking forward to coordinating with Syria in
arranging the visits of the citizens of both countries and
organizing religious or cultural travels between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Iraqi tourist ties are longstanding and the
potential of tourist cooperation between the two sides is great,
he noted.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official voiced hope for reviving the tourist
exchanges as soon as possible to boost the economic development
of the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
The relations between Iraq and Syria which were severed in 1980
due to Damascus's support to Iran in an eight-year Iran-Iraq war
(1980-88) have improved remarkably since a Syrian delegation paid
a visit to Iraq in May, the first in the past 17 years.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the two countries exchanged delegation visits that
led to the reopening of joint borders in June and the signing of
trade protocols as a prelude to political rapprochement.
</P>
