<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G7 Hopes to See Thailand Implement IMF Reform Vigorously </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Group of Seven (G7)
major industrialized nations hope that Thailand would implement an
International Monetary Fund program of reform vigorously, Japanese
Finance Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka said here today.
</P>
<P>
"We expect the Thai authorities to implement vigorously the
Fund program and continue to cooperate with the international
financial institutions," Mitsuzuka told a press conference after a
meeting of G7 financial ministers and central bank governors.
</P>
<P>
"We have agreed on the importance of minimizing contagion, and
we will continue to monitor closely developments in Asian
markets," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai baht has dropped 30 percent since it was floated on
July 2 after Thailand had spent billions of dollars in a vain
effort to defend the currency against speculators. The crisis has
spread to its Southeast Asian neighbors including the Philippines,
Malaysia and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The IMF later arranged a 17.2-billion-US dollar rescue package
to aid the ailing Thai economy in return for a program of reform.
</P>
<P>
Japan's central bank governor, Yasuo Matsushita, said that
although the currency crisis has not settled down and the
short-term economic slowdown is unavoidable, the prospects for the
region are good in the long run as the fundamentals remain
favorable.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Japan's massive external surplus with the United
States, the finance minister admitted that the US concern was
"expressed" at the meeting. "They said as a friend they had
grounds to be worried."
</P>
<P>
The meeting, held prior to the World Bank-IMF Annual Meetings
scheduled for September 23-25 in Hong Kong, was the first one in
Asia for seven years. G7 finance ministers last met in 1990 in
Bangkok, Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Other topics discussed at the meeting included economic
developments in the G7 countries, the recent progress toward the
Economic and Monetary Union in Europe, debt problems facing some
developing countries as well as IMF-related issues.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
