<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asia's Prosperity Means Opportunity for All: Mahathir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad said here today that Asia's prosperity will pose
no threat to the rest of the world and instead, it will bring
opportunities for everyone.
</P>
<P>
"You have nothing to fear from the prosperity and well-being of
Asia; you have everything to gain," Mahathir said in a keynote
speech at a seminar organized by the World Bank and the
International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
"For our prosperity, we contribute to your prosperity and the
rest of the world," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Asia is full of opportunities, not just for Asia, but for
everyone," Mahathir said on the first day of four days of seminars
prior to the annual meetings of the World Bank and the IMF
scheduled for September 23-25 in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir advocated a policy of "prospering your neighbors",
saying: "If you help your neighbors prosper, you prosper along
with them." He cited the win-win case of Japan and Malaysia, in
which Japan gained a huge trade surplus while Malaysia learned
technical know-how and expertise.
</P>
<P>
He lashed out at international speculators who he said stirred
up the recent currency turmoil in Southeast Asia. "Their profits
came through impoverishing others, including very poor countries
and poor people."
</P>
<P>
He strongly attacked this zero-sum game, in which "you win,
others lose. You prosper at the expense of others'
impoverishment."
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian currency ringgit has fallen significantly in
recent weeks, resulting in a de facto devaluation of 20 percent in
the currency turbulence. Mahathir expressed his bitterness that
after 30 years of toil and sweat, Malaysia was pushed back a
decade.
</P>
<P>
One of the tiger economies in Southeast Asia, Malaysia once
served as a model of healthy growth, with an annual GDP growth of
eight percent, inflation down to four percent and no foreign debt.
</P>
<P>
"We have the money but not enough to defend ourselves" when
Southeast Asian tigers were targeted by currency speculators, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Mahathir also blamed "the great powers" for the currency crisis
and said they do not want to see Asia prosper. "If countries in
Europe and North America can be enormously prosperous, we don't
see why we can't be allowed to be a little prosperous," he said.
</P>
<P>
Stressing the differences between Asia and other continents, he
said Asian countries should brush aside what they have been told
to do, and do as they think they should do.
</P>
<P>
"Think of Asia opportunities, and seize them," he concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
