<HEADLINE> U.S. Regrets Cameroonian Oppositions' Poll </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Department of State
has expressed its regret over Camerounian opposition parties
decision to boycott the upcoming presidential election.
</P>
<P>
James P. Rubin, the spokesman of the U.S. Department of State,
said in a written statement Friday, " While this is certainly
their right, a boycott does not further democracy in Cameroon",
adding that violence will solve nothing.
</P>
<P>
The statement said it "regrets that government of Cameroon and
the major opposition political parties are unable to reach an
agreement on reforms necessary to ensure that the upcoming
presidential elections will be free and fair."
</P>
<P>
It said the U.S. government continues to believe that free and
fair elections are essential to Cameroon's future.
</P>
<P>
"We urge both the government and opposition to redouble their
efforts to correct documented problems and find pragmatic
solutions to difference dividing them to permit an inclusive
electoral process," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The three major opposition political parties of Cameroon: The
Social Democratic Front (SDF), The National Union for Democracy
and Progress (NUDP) and the Camerounian Democratic Union (CDU)
announced on September 12 to boycott the presidential elections
scheduled for October 12.
</P>
<P>
They called on the international community to "support the
people of the country in their struggle for basic freedoms and
democracy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
