<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haze Condition Improving in Sarawak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The air quality in
Malaysia's Sarawak State where a state of haze emergency was
declared yesterday improved today.
</P>
<P>
The Air Pollutant Index (API) reading in Kuching, Sarawak's
capital, declined to 446 at 5 p.m. today from 503 at noon,
according to a Department of Environment statement.
</P>
<P>
Cloud-seeding began in Sarawak today, with an Air Force Charlie
130 aircraft used for the operation above the Kuching
International Airport in a bid to create artificial rain,
according to reports from Kuching.
</P>
<P>
However, government clinics in Sarawak have reported a drastic
increase in cases of haze-related diseases such as conjunctivitis
and asthma cases among children just a day after the state was put
on haze emergency, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
Sarawak Medical Department Director Mohamed Taha Arif was
quoted as saying the number of children treated statewide for
conjunctivitis rose more than 10 times from 13 on September 18 to
154 yesterday. Asthma cases among children nearly doubled from 50
to 95 and those of upper respiratory tract infection cases also
jumped from 252 to 390 while bronchitis cases went up from eight
to 10.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Malaysia's National Disaster Relief Management
Committee Chairman Mohamed Rahmat told reporters here today that
the state of haze emergency in Sarawak will be reviewed on
September 22.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, who is the national operations
director, will hold a meeting with relevant ministers to discuss
whether to revoke the declaration, Mohamed said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the haze emergency declared yesterday is still in
force and that even though the API readings in Kuching have gone
down, further monitoring is still required at least for the next
72 hours. 
</P>
</TEXT>
