<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Economy Still in Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, September 20 (Xinhua)-- Ministry of Finance
officials of Sierra Leone Friday disclosed that the economy of
the west African state continues to register a negative growth
with a deficit of over 8.5 million U.S. Dollars as of September 3
this year.
</P>
<P>
According to records available, since the May 25 coup which
overthrew the civilian government, a mere 4.3 percent of monthly
expected revenue of 9.4 million dollors has been registered.
</P>
<P>
"This is because the military government depends on vault
financing," an official from the Finance Ministry, who asked not
to be identifed, said, adding that " This kind of financing is
not only non-sustainble and inflation generating, but also unable
to provide adequate funds for development and recurent
expenditures."
</P>
<P>
During the first four months of 1997, monthly government
revenue averaged 7.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the month of July after the coup, it fell to 406,000
dollars. During peace time, government generated 70 percent of
its revenue from Customs, 16 percent from income tax, two percent
from mining industry, five percent from road user charges and
seven percent from other sources.
</P>
<P>
Due to security and liquidity problems, Customs operation was
grounded as a result of non arrival of vessels.
</P>
<P>
The closure of business and banks hamper operation of the
income tax department, which collected only 16 percent of its
targeted revenue and fell drastically from 759,600 dollars in May
to nil in June but increased to 38.600 dollars in July after the
reopening of few middle level businesses and the state -run
Sierra Leone Commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
The British owned Barclays and Standard Chartered Banks are
still shut.
</P>
<P>
All other revenue generating area are not functioning.
</P>
<P>
The records also showed that while the current average monthly
expenditure was estimated at 9.9 million dollars for 1997, 8.9
million dollars was spent by the military government from mid
June to mid July.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with the government-owned Daily Mail,
Head of State Koroma said, "government revenues are drying up but
expenditures must be met."
</P>
<P>
"We are exercising fiscal and monetary controls and try to
ensure that every cent spent is for a purpose and fully accounted
for," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0095 </DOCNO>
