<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB Economists on Dhaka's Economic Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 10 (Xinhua) -- A recent World Bank study said
that Bangladesh had been relatively stable since the June 1996
elections but the new government had had limited success in
slicing inflation and attracting foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
The study, published this week in Washington by a panel of
World Bank economists on South Asia's integration into the world
economy, noted that the Bangladesh government has yet to tackle
trickier reforms, such as privatization of loss-making public
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The study said that there are many major challenges in
Bangladesh such as the reduction in the fiscal deficit, weak
macroeconomic conditions and high protectionism, a weak legal
system, administrative inefficiency and the restricted role of the
local private sector.
</P>
<P>
The above-mentioned factors have drawn investors' concerns, the
study added.
</P>
<P>
The foreign direct investment (FDI) in Bangladesh originates
mostly from Asia unlike other countries in South Asia where FDIs
also come from other sources, the study said.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh ranks the 106th among 114 developing countries with
regard to openness to trade, the study noted, adding that
Bangladesh is also ranked lowest among five South Asian countries
in matters of market creditworthiness.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
