<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ramos Promises Not to Run for Re-election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Fidel
Ramos said today that he will step down when his term ends next
year and "will not run for re-election."
</P>
<P>
Ramos made the promise upon his arrival in General Santos city,
the Southern Philippines, from a 10-day, four-nation visit.
</P>
<P>
"I am fully satisfied with having served as your president for
one six-year term as mandated in the constitution," President
Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Philippine Constitution, the president serves a
single six-year term and is not allowed to seek re-election.
</P>
<P>
But during the past two years, Ramos' ruling Lakas-NUCD
(National Union of Christian Democrats) and some mass
organizations have been campaigning for charter changes to lift
the term limits of the president and other elective officials.
</P>
<P>
The charter change campaign has met strong resistance from the
opposition parties and the Catholic Church, which are scheduled to
stage an anti-charter change rally in Manila tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
Organizers said that over one million people are expected to
attend the rally, which may bring about political instability in
the country if clashes between pro-charter-change members and
protesters.
</P>
<P>
The government and the military have warned of possible bomb
explosions and attacks by extremists during the rally.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that Ramos is trying to forestall a political
crisis by making his promise upon his return from a trip to
Eastern Europe and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
In his arrival statement, Ramos also said that a survey by his
cabinet indicates that a great majority of people want charter
changes, "but, after the May 1998 elections."
</P>
<P>
The survey showed a ratio of three to one favoring charter
change after the 1998 elections rather than before the elections,
he added.
</P>
<P>
"So, what other good news is there?" Ramos said, "I will not
run for re-election."
</P>
<P>
"As an outgoing president, I will see to it that there will be
an orderly transfer of the presidency and all its powers to my
elected successor, whoever he or she maybe." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
