<HEADLINE> S. Leone Junta Splits Over Ousted President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria, which is in the
forefront of resolving the crisis in Sierra Leone, said Friday
that the military junta became split over whether to restore the
country's ousted president or not.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary Council
(AFRC) in the capital Freetown Friday, 30 of the 40 members moved
for the restoration of ousted president Ahmed Tejan Kabbah, the
Nigerian defense headquarters disclosed.
</P>
<P>
According to defense spokesman Godwin Ugbo, the refusal of 10
AFRC members to reason with the other 30 led to a free for all
brawl among the council men at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The junta has been suffering unanimous international
condemnation since the coup that overthrew the legitimate
government in May.
</P>
<P>
West African countries, supported by the international
community, have enforced economic embargo and sanctions to flush
out the junta.
</P>
<P>
Members of the military government and their families are
refused to leave the troubled country, as one of the sanction
measures.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the 30 council members who called
for restoration of constitutional rule at the meeting had sought
for safe passages for themselves and their families out of the
country as condition for the handover.
</P>
<P>
Captain S. A. Musa, the Chief Secretary of the Sierra Leonean
military government who moved the motion, was quoted as
cautioning the AFRC that " We cannot run a country when both
local and international community are against us".
</P>
<P>
Such persuasive statements from Musa drew negative reactions
from Eldred Collins, Secretary of Trade and Industry, noted the
spokesman, who is the director of defense information.
</P>
<P>
Collins, along with nine other council members, vowed that the
restoration of President Kabbah would be resisted, the spokesman
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
