<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-24 Calls for Reversing Decline of Official Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Group of 24 developing
countries today urged developed nations to reverse the declining
trend of official development assistance (ODA) to the developing
world.
</P>
<P>
"The percentage of combined donor GNP (gross national product)
devoted to ODA has continuously declined over the past 50 years
and in 1996 fell to its nadir," said a communique issued at the
end of the G-24's 57th ministerial meeting here.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, the ministers "emphasized the need to reverse
this declining trend in order to help recipient countries
alleviate poverty and reach sustainable growth," the communique
said.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference later, Antonio Casas Gonzalez, chairman
of the G-24, also said the ministers "emphasized the very
significant contribution of the developing world in the growth of
the global economy."
</P>
<P>
"This should be appropriately reflected in the decision-making
processes of the Bretton Woods Institutions (BWIs)," said
Gonzalez, who is also president of the Central Bank of Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
BWIs refer to the World Bank and the International Monetary
Fund (IMF), both were established under the agreement reached in
Bretton Woods in the United States 53 years ago. The World Bank
and the IMF will hold their joint annual meetings in Hong Kong
next week.
</P>
<P>
While emphasizing the need for adequate technical assistance
and financing assurances to help developing countries to move
toward capital account convertibility, the communique noted that
the liberalization of the capital account should not be made a
condition for the use of the IMF's resources.
</P>
<P>
The communique also warned that the capital account
liberalization process could put additional stress on the
economies that are already straining to adjust to globalization.
</P>
<P>
The ministers welcomed the "timely response" of the IMF to the
immediate problem in South-East Asia and the substantial support
package mobilized by Thailand's neighbors, saying that they are a
demonstration of regional solidarity.
</P>
<P>
The ministers also expressed full support for cooperative
international efforts to combat transnational bribery, money
laundering, and other forms of economic crime.
</P>
<P>
The ministers voiced concern at the slow progress in
implementing the debt initiative for the heavily indebted poor
countries (HIPCs).
</P>
<P>
"While they (ministers) note the preliminary agreements to
implement the HIPC initiative, they call for a timely finalization
 of those agreements in order to allow eligible countries to
benefit from the initiative," said the communique.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G7 Calls for Avoiding Excessive Currency Depreciation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Group of Seven (G7)
industrialized nations, reviewing the recent financial turmoil
that has swept Southeast Asia, said today that "excessive currency
depreciation" should be avoided to prevent the re-emergence of
large external imbalances.
</P>
<P>
"We discussed recent developments in exchange and financial
markets," said a statement issued at the end of a meeting of the
finance ministers and central bank governors of Britain, Canada,
France, Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed that exchange rates should reflect economic
fundamentals and that excess volatility and significant deviations
from fundamentals were undesirable," it said.
</P>
<P>
"In this context we emphasized the importance of avoiding
excessive depreciation where this could lead to the re-emergence
of large external imbalances," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"We agreed to monitor developments in exchange markets and to
cooperate as appropriate," it added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
