<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Call for Gradual Capital Account Liberalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- International financial
experts today called on developing countries to be prudent about
liberalizing their capital accounts.
</P>
<P>
More than a hundred senior bankers and researchers urged
countries to be fully prepared before allowing free inflows and
outflows of capital.
</P>
<P>
They reached consensus on the issue at a seminar on capital
account liberalization here today, which was part of a series of
events before the annual meetings of the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund (IMF) scheduled for next week.
</P>
<P>
Manuel Guitian, director of the IMF Monetary and Exchange
Affairs Department, said that while benefits of liberalizing the
capital account far exceed potential costs, risk-control mechanism
should be in place to reduce the possibility of any financial
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Experts agreed that free capital movements facilitate a more
efficient global allocation of savings and help channel resources
into their most productive uses.
</P>
<P>
But they pointed out that negative results will be possible
without first strengthening prudential supervision over the
banking system and financial market.
</P>
<P>
Governments should establish a sound basis of macro-economic
policy framework, tighten financial supervision and improve the
structure of the economy so as to reduce risks from any sudden
market changes, Morris Goldstein, a U.S. economist, said.
</P>
<P>
It is also necessary to phase the process of capital account
liberalization appropriately and retain proper capital controls in
the transition period, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Figures show that so far all the most advanced economies have
opened their capital accounts while 139 countries have freed
controls on current account transactions.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
