<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Pacific Forum Meeting Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RAROTONGA (Cook Islands), September 19 (Xinhua) -- The 28th
South Pacific Forum ended here this afternoon after adopting a
communique centering on regional trade, security, climate change
and nuclear shipments.
</P>
<P>
Heads of states and governments of the 16 member countries were
meeting here for the past three days to discuss the issues facing
the South Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
In the communique, the leaders "acknowledged the importance of
public accountability to economic development and agreed to
implement legislation, supported by administrative measures to
counteract undesirable financial activities in the region, noting
that such activities undermined development."
</P>
<P>
The forum urged developed states to honor their obligations and
commitments to provide financial assistance to the Pacific island
states.
</P>
<P>
It supported the establishment of the proposed trade office in
the People's Republic of China and welcomed the offer by China to
contribute funding for the office.
</P>
<P>
Climate change was the heated-debated issue at the forum.
However, the final communique said that forum leaders recognized
that participants at the Kyoto Conference in December, where
developed countries are expected to agree mandatory cuts in their
CO2 emissions, may adopt different approaches, but all forum
members are unified in their support of the principles set out in
the communique.
</P>
<P>
They urged all participants of the conference to pursue
vigorously an outcome which would produce the highest level of net
reduction in global greenhouse gas emissions by means of a legally
binding protocol or other legal instrument.
</P>
<P>
Pacific small island nations are particularly concerned that
the rising sea level caused by climate change will bring damage to
their environment and tourist and fishery industries.
</P>
<P>
On radioactive waste shipments, the forum agreed that
"shipments of plutonium and radioactive wastes through the region
posed a continuing concern and agreed to adopt a consistent
position on the issue, taking into account the risks of an
accident occurring and the consequences of such an accident."
</P>
<P>
"It reiterated the expectation that such shipments should be
carried out in a manner which addressed all possible contingencies
and the concerns of relevant countries."
</P>
<P>
The forum noted the efforts of Japan, France and the United
Kingdom in providing information about recent shipment, and
expressed the hope that this would continue.
</P>
<P>
The next forum is to be hosted by the Federated States of
Micronesia at a date to be finalized by the host country in
consultation with the Forum Secretariat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
