<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Theft Rampant in S. African Gold Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- About five billion Rand
(1.1 billion U.S. Dollars) in gold bullion were being stolen a
year in South Africa, local daily Saturday Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
Estimates of the amount of gold stolen from all the mines vary
between 10 and 15 percent of the total production. It was
affecting the viability of the mines, mine managers were quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"If South Africa's gold mines could produce 10 percent more
per annum, we could probably employ 80,000 more miners," James
Watt, a metallurgist, said.
</P>
<P>
Some illegal dealers were earning up to 10,000 rand a day
selling gold nuggets to overseas-based syndicates, informed
sources disclosed.
</P>
<P>
The preferred destination for bootlegged bullion was
Switzerland, but Britain and India also had a passion for the
precious metal, they said.
</P>
<P>
"It is impossible to get an accurate figure, but we estimate
1.6 billion Rand (340 million U.S. Dollars) worth of gold is
ending up in Swaziland alone," said Andre Fourie, operations
manager for security at Gold Fields, a well-known gold producer
in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Most of the gold was reportedly smuggled through customs at
Johannesburg international airport and Durban's airport and
harbor.
</P>
<P>
"We are dealing with crooked miners and crooked security
guards on the mines, and there are a lot of syndicates," said
Superintendent Henk Van Rensburg of the Diamond and Gold Unit in
Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
The highly-organized syndicates had infiltrated nearly every
South African mine and were capable of refining gold, forging
transport licenses and export papers, and accessing foreign
networks to sell their products, Rensburg said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
