<HEADLINE> Arab Foreign Ministers Meet in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 20 (Xinhua) -- A total of 18 Arab foreign
ministers met at the Arab League (AL) headquarters here today to
discuss the crumbling Mideast peace process and the Palestinian
cause.
</P>
<P>
High on the two-day meeting's agenda are Israeli practices in
occupied Arab territories, the Jewish settlement expansion, and
the cut of services to Palestinian refugees due to a financial
crisis facing the U.N. Relief and Work Agency.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will also discuss conditions in the occupied
Syrian Golan Heights, the planned Turkish-Israeli war games,
Israeli occupation of south Lebanon and the situation in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The 108th AL Ministerial Council meeting, chaired by Saudi
Foreign Minister Prince Saud al-Faisal, will also dwell on the
planned U.N. reforms and the Arab demand to have a permanent seat
at the U.N. Security Council as well as a host of other issues of
Arab concern.
</P>
<P>
The session's 44-item agenda includes inter-Arab cooperation
and executive steps to establish a pan-Arab free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser Arafat
will address the inaugural session on the current crisis facing
the peace process and the Israeli suppressive practices against
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
After a four-hour meeting here on Friday night of foreign
ministers from Egypt, PNA, Syria, Lebanon and Saudi Arabia, an
identical stance was adopted on a number of issues, which will be
verbalized into resolutions at today's session, said Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
The diplomats reaffirmed their rejection of the Israeli policy,
their commitment to the land-for-peace principle and Madrid terms
of reference, as well as full support of U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's speech on August 5 in Washington which
outlined a balanced U.S. policy towards the peace parties.
</P>
<P>
Albright left the region on September 15 after visiting Israel,
the Palestinian territories, Syria, Egypt, Jordan, Saudi Arabia and
Lebanon. Her visit is largely considered in the Mideast as a
positive step by the U.S. to revive the peace process.
</P>
<P>
AL Secretary General Esmat Abdul-Meguid said the possibility of
freezing the normalization process with Israel still exists.
</P>
<P>
"This is a principled stance until the Israeli position
demonstrates that there is some change," Abdul-Meguid said in an
interview with the Egyptian Middle East News Agency Friday.
</P>
<P>
This freeze includes putting on hold all steps made to
normalize ties with the Jewish state as part of the peace process
and to boycott multi-lateral negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli negotiations have been deadlocked since
March when Israel began the construction of a Jewish settlement in
East Jerusalem. And the five-month crisis heightened after five
suicide bombings hit Jerusalem on July 30 and September 4 that
killed 25 people and wounded more than 300 others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
