<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swedish Economy Stronger Than Expected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Swedish government expects
the national economy to grow 2.3 percent in 1997 and 3.1 percent
in 1998, up 0.6 percentage points compared to the previous
estimation in the Spring Budget Bill with rapidly increasing
private consumption.
</P>
<P>
Inflation remains low and government finances have developed
more positively than expected, said the government's 1998 budget
bill presented Friday by Swedish Finance Minister Erik Asbrink to
the parliament.
</P>
<P>
It said that the surplus in the balance on current account is
expected to reach 70 billion Swedish kronor (about 9.2 billion US
dollars) in 1998, or approximately 4 percent of GDP (gross
domestic product).
</P>
<P>
Inflation in the country is estimated to be at 2 percent by the
end of this year and drop to 1.5 percent at the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Despite the improved economic situation, the Swedish government
will fail to fulfil its target of halving visible unemployment by
the year of 2000, which would bring unemployment rate down to 4
percent. The figure is now expected to be 4.5 percent in the year
2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
