<HEADLINE> French Press Comment on 15th CPC Congress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Major French newspapers today
commented or carried reports on the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), saying the CPC has shown its
determination to push forward economic reform and drive through
the campaign against corruption.
</P>
<P>
The national daily Le Figaro said if China needs a new team of
leadership having the courage to adapt to the new epoch, the seven
members of the Standing Committee of the CPC Political Bureau have
decided to make up such a team.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that by presenting his six other colleagues in
the Political Bureau in the People's Great Hall today, the CPC
General Secretary Jiang Zemin had no doubt that the new Chinese
leadership can respond to the challenges of the new century.
</P>
<P>
The nomination of Wei Jianxing and Li Lanqing to the Standing
Committee of the Political Bureau also showed the CPC's
determination to fight corruption and further develop economic
cooperation with other countries, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Another national daily Le Monde said in its editorial that six
months after the demise of Deng Xiaoping, the CPC led by Jiang
Zemin is pushing forward economic reform and does not hesitate to
"knock over" the orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the CPC this week decided to let private
capital flow into state enterprises, which it said had been so far
untouched by the reform.
</P>
<P>
It also said that the World Bank and International Monetary
Fund "rivaled each other" in praising the economic achievements of
China and its new decisions on economic reform when they were
holding their annual sessions in Hong Kong this week.
</P>
<P>
"These gestures bring about a good climate. One can better feel
it when taking into account the policy of Chinese government in
Hong Kong and its announcement to reduce customs duties on the eve
of China's admission into the World Trade Organization. All
converge to give the impression that China is anxious... to
integrate itself into the international community," said le Monde.
</P>
<P>
The paper added that the participants of the 15th CPC National
Congress were more representative of all walks of the Chinese
society than before, and that many delegates expressed their views
freely in front of the media.
</P>
<P>
The daily Liberation said that the make-up of the new Chinese
leadership reflects the two "great poles of interests for the
moment" in China: economic reform and the fight against
corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
