<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenyan Govt Chalks Revenue Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Total revenue of the Kenyan
government fell short of the target by 6.3 billion Shillings
(112.7 million U.S. Dollars) during the 1996/97 fiscal year,
according to the latest Quarterly Budget Review.
</P>
<P>
The governmental revenue reached 149.2 billion Shillings (2.7
billion Dollars) in the year, making up 27.5 percent of Gross
Domestic Product. The target was 155.5 billion Shillings (2.83
billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
All major revenue items, such as income tax, customs duty,
excise duty, and value-added tax on imports, under-performed
compared to the targeted levels, said the review made by the
Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
The shortfall on import duties was due to the decline in
import volumes during the second and third quarters of the fiscal
year, even with the appreciation of the Shilling against the hard
currencies.
</P>
<P>
The drop in sales of beer and cigarettes, the two most
important revenue items under the excise tax area, adversely
affected revenue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
