<HEADLINE> Zambia's First AIDS Hospital to Open soon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Zambia's first ever HIV/AIDS
patients' hospital will open in the next two weeks, local mass
media reported today.
</P>
<P>
Proprietor Pola Donck from the Netherlands was quoted as
saying here on Friday that 20 patients could be accommodated at
same time in the 200,000-U.S.-dollars hospital.
</P>
<P>
She said she embarked on the project to serve the people with
AIDS after her brother died for the disease in 1985.
</P>
<P>
"It is just a coincidence that I have found myself in Zambia
for this project. I have come to like the peoople here because of
their hospitality. This is to emphasize the fact the HIV/AIDS
patients deserve care."
</P>
<P>
Donck urged Zambians to talk more about AIDS because "an enemy
you always talk about will ultimately reverse, but if you keep
quiet about it, he will attack you a second time."
</P>
<P>
A Dutch nurse is expected to come and work voluntarily at the
hospital while a resident Catholic nun will also voluntarily
oversee the hospital.
</P>
<P>
Donck will be here for next two years before she finally hands
over the hospital to the local Catholic sisters.
</P>
<P>
Donck's next project is to construct an orphanage also in
Lusaka for children who are victims of collapsing families due to
the deaths of parents from either AIDS or other tragedies of
life. 
</P>
</TEXT>
