<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore's External Trade Grows in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's total trade at
current prices grew by 8.4 percent in August on a three-month
moving average basis, with increases scored in both exports and
imports, the Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB) said today.
</P>
<P>
It said that non-oil domestic exports increased by 7 percent
while re-exports increased by 6.6 percent. Oil exports grew
moderately by 1.9 percent and non-oil imports continued to
increase, by 10 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
On a monthly basis, non-oil domestic exports rose by 5.5
percent. This was the third consecutive month of positive growth,
though slightly lower than the 6.7 percent increase recorded in
July.
</P>
<P>
The TDB said that while domestic exports of semiconductors
continued to expand strongly by 23.1 percent and that of printed
circuit boards assembled increased by 13 percent, export growth of
disk drives moderated to 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, re-exports rose steadily by 7.2 percent on a
monthly basis, due mainly to re-exports of electronics and related
products to the European Union and the United States, it said.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil imports increased strongly by 14.1 percent in the
month, reflecting largely increases in electronics components and
parts, the TDB said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
