<HEADLINE> 50 People Injured in Blast in West Mostar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, September 19 (Xinhua) -- A powerful blast near the
police station in the Croat-controlled western Mostar Thursday
wounded 50 people, the Herzegovina-Neretva Cantonal Interior
Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said that three security guards of the police
headquarters were seriously injured and one of them were
immediately sent to a Croatian hospital by a SFOR (Multinational
Stabilization Force) armoured carrier.
</P>
<P>
The blast destroyed 56 apartments in the building and about 44
cars around the building, said the minister for internal affairs
of Croatia in the Mostar region.
</P>
<P>
The explosion, which was reportedly caused by a car bomb, was
the worst in Bosnia since the Dayton peace accords ended three and
a half years' civil war in 1995.
</P>
<P>
"We are obliged to warn that this act ensued an orchestrated
media campaign against Croats and is the worst in a line of
terrorist acts against Croats who live in Bosnia-Herzegovina,"
said Kresimir Zubak Friday, the Croat member of the
Bosnia-Herzegovina three-member Presidency.
</P>
<P>
Zubak urged the relevant bodies to investigate into the case
and punish the criminals.
</P>
<P>
Mostar, 50 miles southwest of Sarajevo, is divided into the
Croat-controlled west and Muslim-controlled east.
</P>
<P>
Hard-liners of both sides had opposed the joint police force, a
sign of the desire of some to forget the divisions created by
bitter Muslim-Croat fighting in 1993 and 1994.
</P>
<P>
Although the Muslim-Croat war ended in 1994 with the creation
of a US-brokered Muslim-Croat federation, tensions have remained
in Mostar, one of Bosnia's most war-damaged area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
