<HEADLINE> India Dares Suzuki to Withdraw from Joint Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The bitter row between the
Indian government and Japan's Suzuki Motor Corporation over the
management of a joint venture took an ugly turn on Friday as
Indian Industry Minister Murasoli Maran dared Suzuki to withdraw
from the venture, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The dispute flared up on August 27 when the board of Maruti
Udyog Limited, a 50-50 Indian-Japanese joint venture to
manufacture cars, appointed an Indian government nominee, RSSLN
Bhaskarudu, as the company's new managing director.
</P>
<P>
Despite several efforts, the problems between the partners
could not be resolved and Suzuki finally moved to the Delhi High
Court filing a petition to stay the appointment of Bhaskarudu as
managing director.
</P>
<P>
Taking a hard stand on the fight with Suzuki, Industry Minister
Maran said on Friday that the Japanese company "is welcome to walk
out of Maruti Udyog (the joint venture)."
</P>
<P>
He said that the government will continue to support
Bhaskarudu's appointment as managing director of Maruti Udyog.
</P>
<P>
"There are thousands of people waiting," he warned. "All the
major automobile majors in the world are in India. They are
waiting to jump at the opportunity (to replace Suzuki)."
</P>
<P>
Suzuki has contended that according to the agreement between
the Indian government and Suzuki, the managing director's
appointment could be made only on obtaining its concurrence.
</P>
<P>
At a hearing on Friday, the Delhi High Court reserved its order
till Monday on the Suzuki petition challenging the nomination of
Bhaskarudu as managing director.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
