<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Offers 10.5 Million Dollars for Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Britain is to contribute
10.5 million U.S. Dollars to help reduce Uganda's debts to the
African Development Bank (ADB), reported the local daily, The
Monitor, today.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here Friday by the British High
Commission said that unveiling a five-point plan proposed by the
British government to resolve the debt problems of poor
countries, the British government urged other countries to follow
British lead in writing off aid loans to poor countries.
</P>
<P>
The British decision follows an agreement by the World Bank
and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) last year to Uganda's
eligibility as the first country to benefit from the Heavily
Indebted Poor Countries (HIPC) initiative.
</P>
<P>
According to the initiative, the two multilateral financial
institutions together with the regional development banks, will
reduce the value of their outstanding loans to eligible
countries.
</P>
<P>
Under the five-point plan, Britain also pledged to cancel the
remaining debt due to the United Kingdom from lower income
Commonwealth countries.
</P>
<P>
The ADB portion of the debt relief for Uganda will be 23
million U.S. Dollars. But the bank is able to finance only part
of this - some 6.8 million U.S. Dollars from its own resources.
</P>
<P>
Britain's bilateral contribution of 10.5 million U.S Dollars,
together with contribution totalling 5.6 million U.S. Dollars
from Norway and the Netherlands, mean that the cost of reducing
Uganda's debts to the ADB will now be covered in full, the press
release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0134 </DOCNO>
