<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ten Buried Alive as Building Collapses in Nairobi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 20 (Xinhua) -- More than 10 people,
including a pregnant woman, were buried alive Friday after a
three-story building collapsed in Kenya's capital Nairobi, the
East African Standard reported today.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy struck in Eastleigh in northeastern Nairobi around
10:00 a.m.. The building housed a supermarket on the ground floor
and self-contained residential houses on the first and second
floors. Its third floor was still under construction.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 people teamed up with the police and firemen
from Nairobi City Council in a rescue operation that lasted for
hours. But they had only managed to save five people by 1:00
p.m..
</P>
<P>
A one year old infant was the first to be saved from the
debris. Four men were also dug out later taken to hospital.
</P>
<P>
Victims trapped under thick heaps of debris could be heard
crying out for help, but little could be done other than just
continue digging, an exercise which was proving futile when the
rescuers finally reached huge slabs of concrete.
</P>
<P>
The structure was surrounded by extensions which seemed poorly
planned. This hindered the access of bulldozers, crane tractors
and fire engines.
</P>
<P>
Looters had a field day as they stole sodas and gulped them on
the spot. Others carried away radios and televisions before the
police arrived at and guarded the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
