<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indian Central Bank Intervenes to Curb Rupee Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Reversing its role as a
seller of dollars in the last one month, the Reserve Bank of India
(RBI) bought 25-50 million U.S. dollars on Friday to arrest the
appreciation of the rupee, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The central bank stepped in when the Indian currency
strengthened to 36.25 rupees against the greenback.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in the past one month that the apex bank
acted to arrest the strengthening of the rupee.
</P>
<P>
The "reverse intervention" by the RBI sent out a signal that
the informal band is fixed at 36.25-36.60 rupees per dollar.
</P>
<P>
"The two-way intervention has made it clear that the apex bank
has fixed a band to stem volatility in the market which will
enable exporters and importers to cover their positions without
speculations," a corporate treasurer in a private company was
quoted as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
