<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Moves to Curb Cholera in Western Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has
taken actions to contain the spread of cholera disease in Nyanza
Province in western Kenya where the disease had claimed more than
100 lives in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Red Cross Society Friday dispatched a truckload of
drugs to the province and pledged that more assistance will be
sent to combat the spread of the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
A medical team from the Ministry of Health has gone to Nyanza
Province to help contain the disease, and two vehicles were
provided for the disease-prone areas to help transport the
victims from the hinterland to the medical centers.
</P>
<P>
James Mwanzia, Director of Medical Services, was quoted as
saying Wednesday that the medical team would be based in Migori
where they would join local personnel in dealing with the
epidemic which is ravaging the district.
</P>
<P>
The director toured the epidemic-hit areas early this week and
pledged to deploy a large number of medical personnel and drugs
consignment to boost the provincial surveillance teams in
containing the epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Public health officers and provincial administrators have
closed about 1,000 food kiosks, bars and abattoirs across Nyanza
Province in an effort to curb the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Health officers have also banned bathing in rivers, eating at
funerals and hawking of food in open places in the disease-prone
areas such as Muhoroni, Kendu Bay and Homa Bay.
</P>
<P>
The issue was also raised in Kenya's parliament by Ndhiwa MP,
Orwa Ojode, who asked the government to take urgent actions to
contain the spread of the disease in the province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
