<HEADLINE> U.S., Japan Vow to Cooperate Closely in Exchange Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- United States Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin and Japanese Finance Minister Hiroshi
Mitsuzuka today pledged to work in close cooperation on tackling
problems in exchange market.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers met here this morning in advance of the G-7
finance ministers and central bank governors meeting to be held
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said that they exchanged views informally on
various issues to be discussed at the G-7 meeting, including the
current economic situation and economic policies of each country.
</P>
<P>
They reaffirmed during the meeting the importance of
maintaining a strong cooperative relationship in financial issues.
</P>
<P>
Rubin expressed concern that the Japanese economy is weaker
than expected, and the Japanese external surplus is increasing.
</P>
<P>
Mitsuzuka reaffirmed the Japanese government's objective of
achieving a domestic demand-lift growth in Japan and avoiding a
significant increase in its external surplus.
</P>
<P>
In light of the economic situation in Japan, he stated that the
Japanese government will take appropriate measures in consistence
with the structural reform.
</P>
<P>
Sources said that the two ministers reviewed the recent
developments in their respective financial markets, reaffirming
their commitment to cooperating closely in exchange market as
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed on the importance of a successful conclusion
of the WTO financial services agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
