<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moi Criticizes IMF, World Bank for Introducing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan President Daniel arap
Moi complained that the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and
World Bank are introducing new conditions for further Assistance even
when Kenya agreed to restructure the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya Times today quoted President Moi as saying Friday at
Kabarnet town, west Kenya, that the two organizations want the
Kenyan government to divorce itself from the sector.
</P>
<P>
Moi noted that the conditionality is not possible since the
government had a vital stake in such areas as rural electrification.
</P>
<P>
He questioned the call for strict regulations in the energy
sector, including the monitoring of power supply in the national
grid, decrying "too much internal interference" by foreign people
claiming to be friends of the country.
</P>
<P>
Moi accused local organizations like the Federation of Kenya
Employers of colluding with the IMF and World Bank to sabotage
government efforts to initiate reforms in the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
President Moi reiterated that the lapsing of a crucial loan
package by the IMF amounting to 205 million U.S. Dollars was
purely political.
</P>
<P>
Following the IMF decision to suspend the loan to Kenya on
July 31, Moi met and held discussions with high ranking officials
from the two organizations on the restructuring of the energy
sector and other areas.
</P>
<P>
However, even after Kenya met their conditions, Moi said, the
two organizations were still introducing new conditions.
</P>
<P>
The president urged Kenyan people to remain united to be able
to overcome economic blackmail from international organizations
and maintain their dignity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
