<HEADLINE> Williamson Wins Heavyweight Title at Ali Cup Challenge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 19 (Xinhua) -- DaVarryl Williamson of the
United States outpowered his American compatriot Calvin Brock to
take the heavyweight title at the inaugural Mohammad Ali Cup
Challenge in Kentucky on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Williamson got up from his first knock down as an amateur to
stop Brock in the fourth round en route to winning his title.
</P>
<P>
The top-ranked amateur Williamson, twice national champion, was
floored in the first round by a left hook and overhand right from
Brock.
</P>
<P>
He was back on his feet quickly, and became the aggressor in
the second round, bringing a standing eight-count against Brock
with a right uppercut and a flurry.
</P>
<P>
In the fourth round, Williamson dazed Brock with a right,
followed by a combination before the referee stopped the fight
1:13 into the round.
</P>
<P>
However, three of his compatriots lost their championship bouts
to international opponents.
</P>
<P>
Roel Velasco of the Philippines, a silver medalist from the
1996 Olympics, outlasted American fighter Gabriel Elizondo to win
a 28-26 decision in the light flyweight division.
</P>
<P>
Robert Pliev of Russia whipped LeChaunce Shepherd of the United
States 18-8 in the welterweight class, and Brian Magee of Ireland
beat U.S. fighter Jeff Lacy 17-10 in the middleweight bout.
</P>
<P>
In a battle of Americans, Richardo Juarez defeated Cornelius
Lock 17-8 in the bantamweight division.
</P>
<P>
Asan Seksenbaev of Kazakhstan edged Kay Huste of Germany 10-9
in the lightweight fight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
