<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Forms Management System Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has formed a
nation-wide Chemical Management System (CMS) to prevent human beings
and the environment from hazardous chemicals, the local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
A resolution was passed this week in Dar es Salaam at the climax
of a three-day workshop on chemicals management and safety, acting
Government's Chief Chemist Vera Mpore said in an interview with the
local newspaper Guardian.
</P>
<P>
Mpore said that the resolution was reached after realizing that
there was no any other means to prevent human beings and the
environment further from increased hazardous chemicals, apart from
formulating the chemicals' management system.
</P>
<P>
She noted, "It was also felt that in a number of countries,
including Tanzania, there was a need for a harmonized system of
classification, labeling and making of chemicals."
</P>
<P>
After learning that Tanzania was soon becoming a dumping ground of
foreign products unit for human consumption, a committee comprising
various food, chemicals and industrial activists met in February
this year to study a national profile.
</P>
<P>
"It was after going through the national profile when we
concluded that the need to deal with the rampant and hazardous
chemical was unavoidable," Mpore said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fuzhou Bonded Zone Processing Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Three processing companies
have commenced operations in the Fuzhou Bonded Zone in east
China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the companies signaled the zone's increasing
export capacity, and the fact that the zone has emerged as the
export products processing base for Fuzhou.
</P>
<P>
The zone, one of China's 15 free trade zones, has approved more
than 380 projects related to foreign trade, processing, storage
and exhibitions, with said projects involving a combined
investment of 430 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
The zone's foreign trade volume for the first half of this year
amounted to 91.62 million US dollars, up 96.9 percent on last year's
same period.
</P>
<P>
The zone, which neighbors on Mawei Port, one of China's ten
leading ports, has in recent years tapped the full advantages of
international marketing networks and inland raw materials to
develop its processing industry and entrepot trade.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, local sources report that a number of overseas-funded
processing enterprises will go into operation within the year.
</P>
</TEXT>
