<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania, Malawi to Tame Songwe River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania and Malawi is
to carry out a joint feasibility study next month to tame Songwe
river in Mbeya Region to reduce floods during rainy seasons, said
a news dispatch from Mbeya.
</P>
<P>
A five-member team of experts from both countries visited
Mbeya this week to take preliminary studies on how to tame the
river and held talks with Mbeya Regional authorities.
</P>
<P>
The study is aimed at stabilizing the course of the river
which flows into Lake Nyasa (Malawi), the report quoted C.U.
Mphande, an official of the Malawi Ministry of Agriculture and
Irrigation as saying Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mphande added that it will also look into the possibility of
utilizing the river for irrigation and hydro-power facility.
</P>
<P>
Lake Nyasa is shared by Tanzania, Malawi and Mozambique and in
most cases its floods cause havoc to residents living in the
shores of the lake.
</P>
<P>
Songwe river borders Karonga area in Malawi and Songwe in
Tanzania. It sometimes changes borders, diverting its course to
Malawi and in many occasions into Tanzania too. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
