<HEADLINE> Plan to Help African Girls in Science Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Female Education in
Mathematics and Science in Africa (FEMSA) is devising a national plan
of action to promote participation of girls in science subjects.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was revealed Friday in Arusha, northern Tanzania,
by FEMSA coordinator Joseph O'Connor at a consultative meeting of the
UNESCO on girls and women in science and technology in Africa.
</P>
<P>
O'Connor said that the plan will incorporate initially four
countries -- Cameroon, Ghana, Tanzania and Uganda, and it will begin
with national seminars for senior education officers, gender activists
and university representatives.
</P>
<P>
The Arusha meeting was also told that the African Forum for
Children's Literacy in Science Teaching (AFCLIST) is closely
monitoring the science education projects in sub-Saharan countries to
ensure that they effectively promote girls' participation and
performance.
</P>
<P>
Efforts are underway to establish a center of excellence in gender
studies in mathematics, science and technology at the Makerere
University in Uganda, according to a paper titled "AFCLIST and the
promotion of girls' education in science and technology" that was made
public in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The center will, among other things, monitor gender equity within
AFCLIST and develop gender sensitization training.
</P>
<P>
The project will be a joint venture between AFCLIST, the forum
for African Women Educationalists, FEMSA and the University of Oslo,
Norway. 
</P>
</TEXT>
