<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clear Regulatory Framework Vital to Asian Infrastructure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Government efforts are
urged to work out a clearly-defined regulatory framework in order
to accelerate private participation in the long-run,
capital-demanding infrastructure projects, according to a seminar
here today.
</P>
<P>
Several leaders from both public and private sectors took part
in the morning seminar, which focused on "Infrastructure
Development in Asia: Accelerating Private Participation."
</P>
<P>
The World Bank estimates that Asia will require 1.5 to two
billion U.S. dollars for infrastructure development in the next
ten years, and today less then 15 percent of the financing comes
from the private sector. How to move the 15-percent ratio up
turned out to be a hot topic in today's discussion.
</P>
<P>
Montek Ahluwahlia, Finance Secretary of India said: "Government
policies need to be clearly defined to create a regulatory
environment and a level playing field between private and public
sectors in infrastructure development."
</P>
<P>
The Indian official said that Asian governments have recognized
that private participation is necessary not just for lack of
financial resources, but for the purpose of enhancing economic
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
Toyoo Gyohten, president of Japan's Institute for International
Monetary Affairs, listed three concerns in attracting private
investment in infrastructure development -- project risk,
transaction cost and financing problems. He said that weakness in
regulatory framework, frequent government intervention and lack of
coordination between central and local authorities all contribute
to project risk.
</P>
<P>
"The host countries' commitment is the first and foremost
priority," said Gyohten, who once worked for the International
Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
His view was shared by those from the private sector. Karl
Hermann Badman, Chief Financial Officer of the Siemens AG, said:
"A stable legal and regulatory framework is the prerequisite for
implementing infrastructure projects." The other crucial point is
the economic soundness of the project, according to the German
businessman.
</P>
<P>
Gordon Wu, managing director of Hong Kong-based Hopewell
Holdings Ltd., asked Asian governments to grant national treatment
to foreign investors. "Any investment, either domestic or foreign,
is concentrated on creating new wealth. Foreign investors only
take a small fraction of the wealth," said Wu, whose company has
invested widely in power plants, roads and bridges in China and
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
Speakers at the seminar agreed that the recent currency
turbulence in Southeast Asia would not produce a lasting damage to
the infrastructure projects in the region, and would not deter
investors in a long term. But they stressed the importance of
developing domestic financial market, which can speed up the
infrastructure sector.
</P>
<P>
The two-hour discussion on Asian infrastructure was among a
series of seminars, organized by the World Bank and the IMF before
their joint annual meetings, scheduled for September 23 and 25 in
Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Speaks at G-24 Ministerial Meeting  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese finance
official today called on the international community in general,
and the World Bank and International Monetary Fund (IMF) in
particular, to increase cooperation to prevent and alleviate the
adverse impacts of speculative activities to the world economy,
particularly the economy in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
Invited to speak at the 57th Ministerial Meeting of the Group
24, comprising 24 developing countries, China's Vice-Minister of
Finance Liu Jibin said that the massive international capital
flows in developing countries' capital markets can not only
promote economic development, but also bring unstable factors.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the developing countries are required to further
study how to reasonably liberalize and effectively administer
their capital accounts, Liu said. "The recent currency turmoil in
Southeast Asia has once again sent us a warning signal."
</P>
<P>
The IMF should be extremely cautious in promoting opening the
capital account convertibility, and should first assist the
developing countries to study the pressing problems before
liberalizing the capital account, and provide them with technical
assistance and policy advice, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
"We are of the view that, in promoting capital account
convertibility, the Fund should respect the sovereignty of members
and the existing jurisdiction of other international treaties,
allow sufficient flexibility for the members with immature
conditions under the transitional arrangements, and assist them in
proceeding toward capital account convertibility in an orderly and
healthy manner," he said.
</P>
<P>
Liu expressed China's support for an increase in quotas under
the Eleventh General Review of Quotas to strengthen the IMF's
financial capability.
</P>
<P>
In the past decade or so, the share of the developing countries
 in the world economy has constantly increased, he said. However,
he added, their quota share in the Fund and capital share in the
World Bank have been declining.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
