<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO,Tin &AMP; Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of
crude palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week
all higher.
</P>
<P>
The CPO physicals market closed encouragingly this week, on
unexpected late buying on the last trading day, sparked by fresh
covering in the futures.
</P>
<P>
September South closed substantially higher to 1,475 riinggit
(about 491.6 U.S. dollars) per ton, up 105 ringgit (about 35 U.S.
dollars) from last week's close.
</P>
<P>
The market is likely to remain favorable next week on technical
buying support, dealers said, adding that however, further
movement would depend on the performance of the futures market and
the currency factor was also expected to determine movement next
week.
</P>
<P>
Throughout this week, the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM) was
very firm with its price all the way up on renewed buying
interest, hitting a 24-month high at the close.
</P>
<P>
The metal settled the week at 16.44 ringgit (about 5.48 U.S.
dollars) per kg, up 78 sen from last week's close.
</P>
<P>
Local tin gained strong support from overseas buyers as the
metal was cheap based on the depreciating local currency Ringgit
which breached the 3.0000 level to the U.S. dollar on the first
trading day and was quoted at 3.0340/90 to the U.S. dollar on the
final trading day, triggering heavy demand for the local tin.
</P>
<P>
This week's accumulated turnover extended to 643 tons compared
with 545 tons last week.
</P>
<P>
Turnover was dominated by Europeans, Japanese and locals.
</P>
<P>
The strong rise on the London Metal Exchange (LME) also spilled
over to the local front which contributed to the strong gain on
the KLTM.
</P>
<P>
The local metal market is expected to consolidate next week.
</P>
<P>
On the Malaysian rubber market this week, October RSS One was
4.0 sen higher to 260.50 sen (about 86.83 U.S. cents) per kg
compared to last week, while SMR added 2.5 sen to 259.50 sen
(about 86.5 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The local rubber is expected to continue its bullish ways next
week due to the cheaper ringgit and demand from Europe, traders
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
