<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Speaks at G-24 Ministerial Meeting  (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Liu urged the IMF and the World Bank to take full account of
this problem in designing quota distribution and capital
distribution proposals respectively.
</P>
<P>
He said that China appreciates the IMF's unremitting efforts in
addressing the one-time special allocation of special drawing
rights (SDR).
</P>
<P>
"On the premise that the general allocation of SDRs according
to the long-term global needs for international liquidity is not
undermined, we support the Managing Director's latest proposal to
have the one-time special allocation of SDR 21.4 billion," Liu
said.
</P>
<P>
He said that private capital flows to developing countries
reached a record level of 245 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, which
was equivalent to 4.5 percent of developing countries' total
gross domestic product that year.
</P>
<P>
However, Official Development Aid (ODA) declined further, which
was only 41 billion U.S. dollars. Liu said that the role of ODAs
can not be replaced by private capitals. While aid effectiveness
is emphasized, the quantity of aid should not be neglected.
</P>
<P>
Liu urged developed countries, from the long-term standpoint,
to take concrete measures to promptly reverse the declining trend
of ODA, and shoulder the international responsibilities, which
fall squarely on them.
</P>
<P>
For the foreseeable future, infrastructure development of
developing countries will still mainly rely on public sector
investments, Liu said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, while facilitating the private capital flows to
infrastructure sector of the developing countries, the World Bank
should continue to strengthen its direct financial support to the
public sector sponsored infrastructure projects in the developing
countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Liu commended the World Bank and the IMF for their efforts, and
hoped that the creditors concerned, in particular the Paris Club
members, will honor their commitments in a timely manner.
</P>
<P>
With regard to its bilateral debts, he said, China is going to
resolve them through bilateral channels on a case-by-case basis.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
