<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Kuala Lumpur Stock
Exchange (KLSE) closed this week lower with the 100-quality stocks
Composite Index falling 64.24 points to 787.84 from 852.08 last
week.
</P>
<P>
The all-share Emas Index lost 16.88 points to 226.00 from
242.88, the Industrial Index was 116.01 points lower at 1,631.39
as against 1,747.40 and the Second Board Index shed 31.33 points
to 414.58 from 445.91 at last week's close.
</P>
<P>
The weakening ringgit has become a major concern and seemingly
affected sentiment as a whole with players looking for signs of
stability, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
This week saw profit-taking taking its toll on prices for most
of the trading days.
</P>
<P>
Lack of fresh leads and concerns over the weakening ringgit
continued to weigh on prices, particularly on index-linked
counters, leading the market to close broadly lower with the
Composite Index falling below its 800 level.
</P>
<P>
Players were waiting for the index to reach the 760 point level
to take the opportunity to grab cheapened quality stocks, the
dealer said.
</P>
<P>
This week, the mainboard volume was 1.081 billion shares worth
5.048 billion ringgit (about 1.68 billion U.S. dollars) from 1.901
billion shares valued at 8.433 billion ringgit (about 2.81 billion
U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover stood at 183.040 million shares
valued at 1.538 billion ringgit (about 512.66 million U.S.
dollars) against 316.012 million shares worth 2.672 billion
ringgit (about 890.66 million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
And off market deals amounted 139.879 million shares worth
1.208 billion ringgit (about 402.66 million U.S. dollars) compared
with last week's close at 145.903 million shares valued at 810.166
million ringgit (about 270.05 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Consumer products accounted for 81.014 million shares traded,
industrial products 120.274 million shares, construction 113.545
million shares, trading/services 232.443 million shares,
infrastructure 13.041 million shares, finance 237.374 million
shares, hotels 2.689 million shares, properties 137.605 million
shares, plantation 48.022 million shares, mining 5.458 million
shares, trusts 1.213 million shares, closed/fund 799,000 million
shares and loan stocks 20.026 million shares. 
</P>
