<HEADLINE> Anti-Dengue Drive Picks up Speed in Delhi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Delhi health
authorities have speeded up efforts to control the spread of
dengue in the Indian capital, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The local health authorities on Friday ordered removal of all
coolers installed in government offices. Coolers, in which there
are built-in water pools for air conditioning, are believed to be
major breeding points of the dengue-causing aedes mosquitoes in
Delhi.
</P>
<P>
The local health authorities are now planning to even ban
coolers in households if the coolers continue to show high
breeding of mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, restrictions on the dress for school students were
also relaxed on Friday so that the students could come to school
wearing full-sleeved shirts and trousers.
</P>
<P>
The local health authorities heaved a sigh of relief as no new
dengue cases were reported from the Indian capital on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The total number of dengue patients remained at 23. However,
the virus now seems to be traveling to the south of the capital
with three confirmed cases being reported from South Delhi on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The posh colonies in South Delhi, where many coolers were
installed, were the worst hit by the dengue epidemic last year
which claimed hundreds of lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
