<HEADLINE> Tung Chee Hwa Calls for Early Inclusion of China to WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee
Hwa of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) today
urged the international community to work for an early accession
of China to the World Trade Organization (WTO.
</P>
<P>
China becoming a member of the WTO is a very important part of
a liberal world trading system and will be beneficial to all sides
of the WTO, Tung told participants in a series of seminars
organized by the World Bank before the annual meetings of the Bank
and the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
"I hope this to happen sooner rather than later," Tung said
when addressing the seminars' opening session this morning.
</P>
<P>
World Bank President James Wolfensohn presided over the opening
session of the seminar program, which will run for four days with
participants expected to exceed 6,000.
</P>
<P>
The program, with the theme "Asia and the World: Capital,
Competitiveness, and Community", will include some 40 highly
interactive sessions, in which global experts will present a wide
range of perspectives for audience discussion.
</P>
<P>
Wolfensohn said that the seminars will focus on areas including
finance and capital markets, infrastructure development,
governance and sustainable development, regional and country
opportunities, and China's partnership in world development.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa said that the annual meetings being held in Hong
Kong are a "vivid testimony" to Hong Kong's status of a world
economic and financial center, and also to Hong Kong's prosperity
and stability.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has witnessed rapid economic growth for the past
decades and become one of the most dynamic regions in the world,
he noted, adding that Hong Kong will continue to play an active
part in world growth and development.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions after his speech, Tung expressed concerns
about the financial crisis in Southeast Asian countries, but held
that the stock market of Hong Kong will not be affected heavily by
 the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong's stock market will maintain stability as it has
drawn lessons from the previous crash in the late 1980s and enjoys
a sound basis in the respects of market rules and market
operation, Tung said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
