<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commonwealth Ministers Call for More Openness from WB, IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Finance ministers from five
Commonwealth countries, including Britain, called for greater
openness by the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) in their debt sustainability analyses.
</P>
<P>
Addressing at a news conference at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center this morning, they, representing 53
member-countries of the Commonwealth of Nations, also called on
the World Bank to look at the position of severely indebted
countries whose debts are owed primarily to multilateral
institutions so that they have as much chance as others of early
and full debt relief.
</P>
<P>
Chairing the press conference, Commonwealth Secretary General
Emeka Anyaoku said all members of the organization would continue
to pay attention to debt issues and provide assistance in
preparing debt sustainability analyses.
</P>
<P>
Present at the press conference were also Gordon Brown, British
Chancellor of the Exchequer, Vasant Bunwaree, Mauritian Minister
of Finance, Trevor Manuel, South African Minister of Finance,
Brian Kuei Tung, Trinidad and Tobago's Minister of Finance, and
Gamini Peiris, Sri Lanka's Minister of Justice and Constitutional
Affairs and Deputy Minister of Finance.
</P>
<P>
Anyaoku said that the finance ministers of the Commonwealth
meet annually for discussing urgent issues prior to the annual
meetings of the World Bank Group and the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The ministers arrived in Hong Kong early this week for the
WB/IMF meeting, directly from the annual meeting of the
Commonwealth Finance Ministers which was held in Mauritius on
September 16-17.
</P>
<P>
At the Mauritius meeting, the ministers discussed a wide range
of issues, including the world economic situation, IMF and World
Bank issues, multilateral debt, the political process and
management of economic change, the private capital flow issues and
cooperation between all the Commonwealth member-countries, Anyaoku
said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the press conference, Gordon Brown briefed about
his new proposals on the Heavily-Indebted Poor Countries (HIPCs)
Initiative, called the Mauritius Mandate, which seeks to
enable all HIPC countries to have embarked by 2000 on the process
of securing a sustainable exit from their debt problems.
</P>
<P>
The Mandate also aims by the millennium to have firm decisions
on the amounts and terms of debt relief for at least
three-quarters of the eligible poor countries, and will help up
to 300 million people living in the world's poorest countries and
contribute to the international target of halving by 2015 the
proportion of the world's population living in absolute poverty,
Brown said.
</P>
<P>
Four other finance ministers, in their turn, stressed the need
to accelerate implementation of the HIPC Initiative and strengthen
cooperation between the well-developed countries and the
less-developed ones. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Approves First Project Financing in Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Export-Import
Bank today approved its first project financing on the African
continent for the 210 million U.S. dollars sales of equipment and
services for the Jorf Lasfar Power Project in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
During the construction phase of the project, the Ex-Im Bank
will guarantee political risk. Upon project completion, the Bank
will either replace the guarantee with a direct loan, or continue
to provide political risk protection.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. ABB Energy Ventures, Inc. and CMS Generation are two
sponsors of the project which, when complete, will supply over 30
percent of Morocco's electricity needs.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. companies will build, own and operate two 350-megawatt
coal-fired electrical generating units for the Jorf Lasfar power
plant.
</P>
<P>
The latest transaction brings the total authorizations of the
Ex-Im Bank's 3-year-old Project Finance Division to more than five
billion dollars. Project finance authorizations are expected to
hit a record 2.6 billion dollars for the fiscal year 1997, which
ends on September 30.
</P>
<P>
The Ex-Im Bank is a federal government agency that backs U.S.
exports. In the past five years, the Bank has authorized a total
of 65.6 billion dollars of financing involving more than 10,000
transactions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0171 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official on Anti-Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official
said here today that the anti-corruption measures taken by the
World Bank and the International Monetary Fund (IMF) should be
held strictly within the ambits of their operations.
</P>
<P>
Invited to speak at the 57th ministerial meeting of the Group
24, composed of developing countries, Chinese Vice-Minister of
Finance Liu Jibin said that corruption is a global phenomenon and
both developing and developed countries need to take actions to
combat corruption.
</P>
<P>
However, anti-corruption is an internal affair of a sovereign
country and the content of anti-corruption far exceeds the
operations mandates of both Bretton Woods Institutions, Liu
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He said that developed countries should not use development
assistance as an excuse to interfere in developing countries'
domestic policies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, when helping the developing countries, the
multilateral development institutions should strictly adhere to
their respective Articles of Agreements and mandates, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Any encroachment on non-economic activities will not only
damage the images of these institutions, but also shake the
members' confidence in them, Liu added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
