<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong's Prosperity to Continue: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's prosperity will
continue under the "One Country, Two Systems" concept, said Donald
Tsang, financial secretary of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) of China here today.
</P>
<P>
At a breakfast briefing, Tsang said that a few months ago, the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) classified Hong Kong as an
"advanced economy", which was a vote of recognition of Hong Kong's
economic performance.
</P>
<P>
"Now the World Bank and IMF are holding their Annual Meetings
in the Hong Kong SAR. This is a vote of confidence in the HKSAR,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Under the Basic Law, he noted, the HKSAR government has full
autonomy in formulating its own monetary and financial policies.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to safeguard free flow of capital and the
Hong Kong dollar remains the only legal tender in Hong Kong as
before," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the U.S. dollar link is still being maintained and
the stronghold for maintaining the link is the combined assets of
the Exchange Fund and the Land Fund totaling 81 billion U.S.
dollars at the end of July 1997.
</P>
<P>
Tsang said that before Hong Kong's return to China, there were
skeptics who casted doubt on whether the guarantees enshrined in
the Basic Law would be honored at all. Facts have dispelled such
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
"Business is as usual here. The strong feeling of stability
and enthusiasm is palpable everywhere you go in Hong Kong," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"I am confident that the liquidity, the transparency and sound
regulation will continue to be the underlying strength of Hong
Kong's market," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that with the rapid economic growth in the Chinese
mainland, Hong Kong's role as China's international financial
center is expected to grow in parallel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
