<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sixth U.S. Military Plane Crashes in a Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 19 (Xinhua) -- A U.S. Air Force B-1
bomber on a training mission today crashed in the northwestern
state of Montana with all four crew killed, adding the number of
military air crashes to six in seven days.
</P>
<P>
The B-1 crashed at about 2:55 p.m. local time in the corner of
southeast Montana, near the state line with Wyoming when it was
flying out of Ellsworth Air Force Base. Causes for the crash are
still unclear.
</P>
<P>
The B-1, which can carry up to 84 conventional 250-kg bombs and
an undisclosed number of nuclear weapons, costs more than 200
million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Pentagon ordered a halt to all military
training flights for one day next week for safety review after
five air crashes in four days.
</P>
<P>
Earlier today, the U.S. Air Force issued a statement, saying
that it will ground all training flights next Friday.
</P>
<P>
"The purpose of the stand down is to give those who fly and
maintain U.S. military aircraft time to focus on that goal, making
flying as safe as we possibly can," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. Air Force C-141 transport plane flying from Namibia
collided with a German military plane off the coast of Africa last
Saturday, killing 31 people.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, an Air Force F-117A stealth fighter flying at an air
show near a Baltimore suburb crashed in a residential area after a
piece of the plane broke off. A U.S. Navy FA-18 crashed in Oman in
the Middle East, killing the pilot on the same day.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, a Marine FA-18D Hornet fighter jet crashed in North
Carolina's Pamlico Sound during a practice bombing run, killing
the two pilots.
</P>
<P>
The following day saw two Air National Guard F-16s collide off
the coast of New Jersey; one crashed into the Atlantic, the other
landed safely. The three pilots survived.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military has lost 55 aircraft in air accidents in the
past fiscal year. It lost 67 last year, 69 in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
