<HEADLINE> Thailand Proposes to Set Up Asian Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has proposed to set
up an Asian fund to restore the region's financial stability, but
the fund seemed to have a long way to go as ASEAN finance
ministers postponed a decision on it.
</P>
<P>
Finance ministers from the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) said Friday at the conclusion of the first
Asia-Europe finance ministers' meeting held here that further
discussion and the participation of key economies in Asia will be
needed.
</P>
<P>
The ministers had not formalized cooperation to deal with
Southeast Asia's financial crisis as they still need the
International Monetary Fund to play a key role, Thai Finance
Minister Thanong Bidaya said.
</P>
<P>
Finance ministers from Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam discussed the matter
late Thursday, but the discussions were inconclusive, local
newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Deputy Prime Minister and Finance Minister Anwar
Ibrahim Friday said that Thailand's fund proposal received
support, but further discussions on the matter are needed and East
Asian economies should be involved.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN finance ministers will meet again early next month in
Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, before the ASEAN economic ministers'
meeting. The establishment of the fund is expected to be among the
topics for discussion at the meeting.  
</P>
