<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmland Protection Effective in South China City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, the capital of
south China's Guangdong Province, has made noticeable achievements
in protection of its farmland by resorting to administrative,
economic and legal measures.
</P>
<P>
The city increased its total farmland areage by approximately
880 hectares from last year to the end of June, compared to a
decrease in farmland acreage over previous years.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou had a total of 168,650 ha of arable land at the end
of 1996, a per-capita average of less than 0.025 ha, far less
the national average. So it began to take active measures to ban
non-agricultural use of land.
</P>
<P>
Since 1991, the city has cultivated 13,756 ha of land, 6,225 ha
of which are used for farming, to basically balance the increases
and decreases of farmland.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the city has charged 8.5 billion yuan for the
land-use rights for 2,531 ha of land in urban areas over the past
five years, which are mainly spent on infrastructure and land
improvement for farming.
</P>
<P>
To speed up land management according to law, the city of
Guangzhou has also worked out 16 codes, regulations and policy
documents concerning land protection, and dealt with more than 200
cases in violation of land use, saving a total area of 530 ha.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
