<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Exports to Britain Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 20 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's exports to
Britain in the first half of this year were 11.5 billion rupees
(195 million U.S. dollars), up 11 percent over the same period of
last year, according to the latest government statistics.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka enjoyed a trade balance with its imports from Britain
standing at 10 billion rupees (169 million dollars) from January
to June this year. In the corresponding period last year, it
imported 6.7 billion rupees (113 million dollars) of British
goods.
</P>
<P>
The statistics said that the increase of trade was a reflection
of continuing strong demand on both sides.
</P>
<P>
The most popular Sri Lankan goods in Britain is clothing, while
a wide range of British goods and services, most notably cereals,
power generating and telecommunications equipment, medicines and
paper products, are easy to find market in Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
Local economic analysts said this year's stronger demand in Sri
Lanka for foreign goods was a sign of better economic conditions
in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
