<HEADLINE> Frenchman Pioline's Injury Gives Belgium 2-0 Lead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Frenchman Cedric Pioline
twisted his back to surrender to Johan Van Herck on Friday, giving
Belgium a 2-0 lead in the Davis Cup tennis qualifying in Ghent,
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the hope looked faint for France to stay in the Davis
Cup's elite World Group.
</P>
<P>
Belgian top player Filip Dewulf strolled to a 3-0 victory over
Fabrice Santoro with his powerful forehand. Dewulf, who ranked
39th, sent an ace with the final ball to finish 6-1, 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
Pioline, top French player, was once seemly cruising to an easy
win as the 1997 Wimbledon finalist took the first two sets 6-4,
6-2.
</P>
<P>
As Van Herck fought back to take the third set 7-5 with the
home spectators behind him, Pioline appeared to have twisted his
back in returning serve. Although he struggled on into the fourth
set, he had to threw in the towel at 4-1 down.
</P>
<P>
Pioline was scheduled to play the doubles match Saturday before
taking on Dewulf in the reverse singles Sunday. 
</P>
