<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania Hosts Anti-Crime Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from 18
European countries ended a three-day meeting here today on how to
combat organized crimes, terrorism and corruption especially in
the Balkans and the Black Sea region.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the United States, Turkey, the United Nations
and the INTERPOL also attended the conference.
</P>
<P>
The participants discussed ways to strengthen cooperation in
anti-crime operations and to improve legislation in individual
countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the conference, Romanian INTERPOL liaison officer
Ion Stefanut said that organized crimes include drug trafficking,
human and arms smuggling, illegal trading of radioactive materials
and money laundering. Romania has become one of the main conduits
for drug trafficking, he said.
</P>
<P>
Romanian President Emil Constantinescu also pledged in a
message to the meeting that his country will do all it can to
crack down on organized crimes and corruption. 
</P>
