<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four-Party Meeting on Korea Issue Ends Without Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 19 (Xinhua) -- The second round of
four-party preparatory meeting on the Korea issue ended here this
afternoon without reaching an agreement.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meeting, involving China, the United States, the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) and the Republic of
Korea, was designed to make preparations for a plenary session on
peace in Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the meeting said that the four delegations
conducted wide-ranging and in-depth discussions in an effort to
define an agenda for the formal talks.
</P>
<P>
They reached certain common understanding on some of the issues
discussed but were still deeply divided on the agenda issue, the
sources said, adding that the parties will continue to consult
with each other.
</P>
<P>
Local press reports quoted a DPRK official as saying that the
parties have failed to reach agreement on the agenda of the
conference, not because of the lack of will. "The only thing we
need here is patience and time," he said.
</P>
<P>
A U.S. official told reporters after the meeting that the
participants had made "some slight progress" but clearly it was
insufficient to begin official talks of the four parties.
</P>
<P>
He said the delegations worked very hard to explore a number of
options to resolve the differences, but "regretfully" serious
attitude still lacked during the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Asked if there are plans for further meetings, he said that
"the offer for peace talks is still on the table, but we have no
plans for further meetings."
</P>
<P>
"We have an established channel which is available for the use
of either side", he added.
</P>
<P>
The first round of preparatory talks was held last month, also
in New York. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
