<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Funds Help to Improve Red Soil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 20 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangxi Province
has made tremendous advances over the last decade in improving the
productivity of its red soil, "China Daily" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Jiangxi has a tropical climate with high temperatures and
humidity. A high mineral content, especially of iron and aluminum,
and man's destruction of the environment gradually made the soil
acid, sticky and porous.
</P>
<P>
The level of organic matter in the soil dropped and people
eventually gave it the name "red desert" since it was such poor
land. This red soil accounts for 64.8 percent of the total
province, a higher percentage than in any other provinces south of
the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, large scale and scientific exploitation and
utilization of Jiangxi's red soil began in earnest. In 1986 the
first phase of the project was launched. It involved 276.48
million yuan (33.3 million US dollars), including a 30 million
dollars loan from the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
The first phase covered an area of 20,000 hectares and included
land reclamation, crop planting, agricultural infrastructure
improvement, poultry raising, processing agricultural produce,
scientific training, relocation of some farmers to mountainous
areas, etc.
</P>
<P>
The project used a family farm concept, with production carried
out by family units. A system of independent business accounting
gave the farmers sole responsibility for their losses and profits,
promoting the farmers' initiative.
</P>
<P>
The project promoted several changes in agricultural
management: from a low standard exploitation to a high standard
comprehensive management, from spontaneous utilization to planned
exploitation of suitable scale, from extensive farming to
intensive cultivation.
</P>
<P>
The first phase of the red soil reclamation project was
completed in 1990, taking 50 months instead of the 72 months
specified in the loan agreement. The ecosystem was optimized. The
forest coverage rate rose from 18 percent to 33 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
