<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Successfully Regulates Domestic Grain Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 20 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government has
been quite successful in regulating and controlling its domestic
grain market, today's "China Daily" reported.
</P>
<P>
Since grain production directly affects people's livelihood,
prices must be regulated by the state when market influences are
negative.
</P>
<P>
Major measures include the adoption of the policy of protective
purchase pricing and the establishment of a grain risk fund,
according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
In addition, to strengthen the function of the local purchasing
departments as the state's major distribution channel for
stablizing the price, the government opened its other hand, filled
with money -- thus removing the fear of further losses.
</P>
<P>
The grain risk fund, set up in 1994, plays an active role in
maintaining reasonable amounts of grain in reserve and reinforcing
the government's ability to regulate grain markets.
</P>
<P>
Up to August this year, the government-owned grain purchasing
departments had purchased 12 billion kilograms of summer grain,
5.7 billion kilograms more than what were collected over the same
period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
