<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba's Decentralization Policy Helps Export Recovery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Cuba's decentralization policy
has helped the recovery of its exports, said Cuban Foreign Trade
Minister Ricardo Cabrisas.
</P>
<P>
The decentralization policy allowed 281 local firms to be
engaged in international trade and other important trade
mechanisms to operate such as bonded warehouses, industrial parks
and duty-free zones, he said in an article published by the Granma
Daily today.
</P>
<P>
There are some 570 representative offices of foreign firms in
the country, which play an important role in the exporting sector,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged the state firms to increase and diversify
the trade of non-traditional products, which are expected to earn
some 300 million U.S. dollars in export revenue in 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
