<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0216 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-US Summit to Accelerate China's TWO Accession: Ruggiero </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 19 (Xinhua) -- World Trade Organization (WTO)
Director-General Renato Ruggiero said here today that he hopes the
upcoming summit between Chinese and U.S. leaders will accelerate
China's accession to the world body.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin and U.S. President Bill Clinton
are scheduled to meet next month in the United States.
</P>
<P>
"I certainly hope that President Jiang's meeting with President
Clinton will accelerate China's accession," Ruggiero told
Xinhua. "To this point China has made great strides in preparing
itself for accession to the WTO, but more work needs to be done."
</P>
<P>
Ruggiero believes that the time for China's accession will be
ripe when all the parties to the negotiation can agree on the
terms.
</P>
<P>
When asked if China should join the WTO as a developing country
or as a developed country, Ruggiero said that China is "both a
developing country and a developed country."
</P>
<P>
"Certainly, a visitor to the Pudong Development Area (of
Shanghai) would come away with the impression that China is a
highly advanced developing country. The skyscrapers of Shanghai
and Beijing give the same impression," Ruggiero explained.
</P>
<P>
"But, much of China, particularly in the western provinces, is
quite poor and would certainly be classified as a developing
region."
</P>
<P>
So one has to judge the Chinese economy sector by sector and
case by case and should not take a one-sided approach, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Ruggiero has visited China several times, a country he thinks
interesting with both thousands of years of history and modern
dynamism which truly makes it "a country of the future". During a
visit to China last April, he visited some relatively poor regions
besides Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
"The deepest impression left on me by my visits has come from
the Chinese people themselves, who are extraordinary in their
energy and hospitality," Ruggiero said. "The changes that I have
encountered on each visit are remarkable. In fact the China of
today is very different from the China of my first visit. These
differences can be seen in virtually every aspect of the Chinese
society." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
