<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-19 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: A Desperate Cry for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEL AVIV, September 19 (Xinhua) -- Three Israeli soldiers stab
to death a Palestinian boy during a night search, and the boy's
father revenges by slaughtering an Israeli couple on their wedding
night.
</P>
<P>
Scores of people are blown into parts in a bombing attack, and
others who are driven crazy slay a laborer mistaken as the
terrorist.
</P>
<P>
Bleeding. Revenge. Killing. All makes a common scene between
the Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
But the scenes are not real in themselves -- they are from
"Murder," a new show being played at Tel Aviv's Cameri Theater to
full houses and shed upon the spotlight of the media and even the
political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
Playwright Hanoch Levin and director Omri Nitzan said they are
attempting to drive home a message to both the Palestinians and
Israelis: murder spawns murder, violence begets violence and the
victims on both sides are innocent -- and peace is the solution.
</P>
<P>
The play was written amid consecutive violent events a year ago.
</P>
<P>
At least 25 people have died in violence since last July,
hundreds since the Oslo peace agreement reached four years ago,
and tens of thousands, or maybe more, for generations, while
neither Palestinians nor Israelis would possibly give up their
claims of rights over the same piece of land.
</P>
<P>
The play was staged at the darkest time for the four-year-old
Middle East peace process, which is shadowed by Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's hardline policy towards the
Palestinians and radical Islamic fighters' bombing plots, with
each factor founding on the other in a vicious circle.
</P>
<P>
With hopes for peace progress evaporating one after another,
there has even been a talk on the possibility of a full-fledged
war between the Palestinians and Israelis.
</P>
<P>
"You and I and the very next war,
</P>
<P>
for us all a blessed thing.
</P>
<P>
You and I and the very next war,
</P>
<P>
perfect peace it will bring," the dying Israeli bride and groom
sing.
</P>
<P>
Shimon Peres, former Labor Prime Minister and one of the
leading architects of the Israeli-Arab peace process, lauded the
anti-war theme. "The aim of the play is to strongly reflect the
opposition to war," he said in an interview with Xinhua after
seeing the play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
