<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Hails Handgun Control Law Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton today said a study by the Center to Prevent Handgun
Violence confirms "what we've known all along" -- the Brady gun
law "is helping to keep guns out of the hands of criminals."
</P>
<P>
The anti-gun law is named after former press secretary James
Brady, who was seriously wounded in the assassination attempt on
President Ronald Reagan. It was passed in 1993 after bitter
congressional battles.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement, Clinton said that while the Supreme
Court ruled against background checks to implement the Brady law,
many states are conducting the checks voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-seven states in the country have their own Brady laws.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the president said the study shows the Brady law
has worked to help disrupt illegal gun trafficking patterns,
making it more difficult for gun traffickers to do business.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
