<DOCNO> XIE19970920.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-19 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feature: A Desperate Cry for Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"There are three parties in reality: You (Palestinians), We
(Israelis) and War. We want to have the coexistence between two of
them and not all three of them: only You and We," he said.
</P>
<P>
Former Israeli Ambassador to New Zealand Nissan Krupsky told
Xinhua that "It (the play) shows you the right direction. We are
not in the right direction now, the directors (of the play) want
us to move the (peace process) in the right direction."
</P>
<P>
The only way to end violence is to push the peace process
forward as strongly as possible, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
A 15-year-old actress in the play, who only gave her name as
Ruthy, said she was pessimistic about the current peace
situation. She criticized the politicians for just talking instead
of taking actions.
</P>
<P>
"We don't know what is the answer, we cannot predict the
future," she said, adding that she and her colleagues did not
hate the Arabs despite the recent suicide bombings in Jerusalem
that killed dozens of people.
</P>
<P>
The play, performed by a group of talented Jewish and Arab
actors, is just one of the peace activities witnessed in the
country recently. Over 10,000 Israeli peace activists gathered
here five days ago to celebrate the fourth anniversary of the
signing of Oslo accords and demand the government to keep the
peace process going ahead.
</P>
<P>
Levin and Nitzan have been awarded "Theater Man of the Year" by
the largest-circulated Israeli daily Yediot Ahronot for the
play. 
</P>
</TEXT>
