<DATE_TIME> 1997-09-20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Congress Gives Clinton Power to Kill B-2 Purchase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 19 (Xinhua) -- U.S. House-Senate
negotiators on the purchase of more B-2 bombers today agreed to
let President Bill Clinton, who opposes the purchase, make the
decision.
</P>
<P>
In completing work on a 247.5 billion U.S. dollars defense
bill, lawmakers also voted to cut off money for the Bosnia
peacekeeping mission by next June unless Clinton comes to Congress
with reasons why the troop deployment should be extended.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has said repeatedly that the Air Force has higher
priorities than the B-2 and can get by with the 21 aircraft
already in service or on order.
</P>
<P>
The legislation completed by members of House and Senate
defense appropriations subcommittees still must win full committee
and floor approval before going to the president.
</P>
<P>
But such major compromises are seldom changed in the final
steps toward passage of a bill.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the House voted narrowly to add 331 million
U.S. dollars that could be used to begin buying as many as nine
more B-2 bombers in the coming years. One B-2 is roughly two
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Clinton had sought 174 million U.S. dollars to continue
modernization and upgrades on the existing B-2 fleet, which cost a
total of 44 billion U.S. dollars to develop and build.
</P>
<P>
Under the compromise, the defense bill would provide a total of
331 million U.S. dollars and it would be up to Clinton to decide
whether to use the money for new aircraft or for modernization of
the existing fleet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
